<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Launches Arab Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) today
announced the implementation of the Arab free trade zone from
January 1, 1998, a prelude to an Arab common market.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid told a press conference
here that "a new era for the Arab nation" has begun, asserting
that the implementation of the zone is the foundation stone of
realizing the dream of Arab economic integration.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that Arab countries will enter the 21st century
as one economic bloc, beginning with setting up the free trade
zone to ensure the flow of Arab goods without restrictions,
customs or other fees," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Arab free trade zone is expected to herald an Arab common
market over 10 years with the liberalization of tariffs in the
Arab world. The accumulative Arab GDP is no more than 529 billion
U.S. dollars and inter-Arab trade accounts for merely 8 percent of
Arabs' trade with the world.
</P>
<P>
Customs between members will be cut 10 percent a year in the
coming decade and will be eliminated by the end of 2007 when the
Arab common market comes into being, said Abdul-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
He voiced conviction that the Arab market will find a place
among other great economic groups.
</P>
<P>
The idea of an Arab common market was first floated in the
1950s and a June 1996 Arab summit called for free trade zone be
established by 1998.
</P>
<P>
The prospective market is expected to group 18 members of the
22-member Arab League, namely Bahrain, Egypt, Iraq, Jordan,
Kuwait, Lebanon, Libya, Morocco, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia,
Somalia, Sudan, Syria, Tunisia, United Arab Emirates, Yemen and
the Palestinian self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
