<HEADLINE> Profile of Pak President-Elect Rafiq Tarar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's president-elect
Justice (Retd) Rafiq Tarar will be sworn in the ninth Head of the
State of this south Asian nation since its inception in 1947.
</P>
<P>
Tarar, nominee of the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (PML) led
by Prime Minister Nawazsharif, swept the Presidential polls
Wednesday by securing 374 votes out of 457 votes.
</P>
<P>
Tarar, born on November 2, 1929, in a small village in Punjab,
hails from a relatively humble origin. He got rich experience in
his 31 years of public service.
</P>
<P>
He is noted for his legal scholarship, honesty and devotion to
justice. Tarar had his schooling in Ghakkar Mandi, Punjab
Province, from where he completed his primary education and did
his matriculation in 1945 from Government Islamia High School,
Gujranwala in Punjab Province.
</P>
<P>
Rafiq Tarar got his law degree from Punjab University Law
College in 1951 and started his legal practice in Gujranwala. In
October 1966, he was appointed as Additional Sessions Judge and
served in the same capacity in two district courts in Punjab
Province.
</P>
<P>
He was elevated to the Lahore High Court in 1974 and served as
a member of the Election Commission of Pakistan from 1980 until
his elevation as Chief Justice of the Lahore High Court on
December 13, 1989.
</P>
<P>
Tarar was elevated to Pakistan's Supreme Court in January 1991,
and was part of the 11-member bench, which restored the Nawaz
government in May 1993. He was also a member of the three-member
inquiry commission headed by Justice Shafiur Rehman set up to
probe the death of former chief of army staff General Asif Nawaz.
</P>
<P>
He retired in October 1994, and was elected as a senator on PML
ticket in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
Though, Tarar is becoming president after only 10 months in
active politics, he brings with him a rich experience of 31 years
of public service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
