<HEADLINE> Feature: HK People Celebrate New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- John Hall, an engineer who
came to Hong Kong two months ago, joined thousands of Hong Kong
people Wednesday evening in celebrating the first new year after
the handover at Victoria Park, Causeway Bay, where a family fun
carnival was being staged.
</P>
<P>
"We have just arrived. We enjoy the performance," he said,
pulling his wife in his arms. The couple were pushing to a stage
for a better look at an ongoing peacock dance.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of seats under the temporary stage were already packed
with people, with more standing behind the railing or watching a
big screen live televising the performance.
</P>
<P>
Programs started at 8:30 PM (0:30 PM GMT) Wednesday, but people
were pouring in about an hour earlier for the traditional carnival
ushering in the new year.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Provisional Urban Council (PUC), the New
Year's Eve Family Fun Carnival is Hong Kong's largest outdoor
party providing four hours of non-stop entertainment for all age
groups.
</P>
<P>
The six football pitches of the park were decorated as a
spectacular carnival, with glamorous setting including the music
stage, dance and fringe stage, big top disco, nostalgic ballroom
dance tent and the children's fun corner.
</P>
<P>
At the music stage, the China Armed Police Blue Band from
Beijing were playing jazz music. The uniformed band plays the
national anthem in the national flag raising ceremony at
Tian'anmen Square. Their maiden show in Hong Kong won warm
applause from the audience.
</P>
<P>
The dance and fringe stage features the incredible performance
by the great American magician and comedian Peter Gross, country
and western dance by Joseph and Mark, also from the United States,
as well as the "Beyond 1997" showcase featuring Chinese dance,
ballet, cha-cha and modern dance by the City Contemporary Dance
Company, a local troupe.
</P>
<P>
Young people were clustering in the disco where DJs were
offering hit music and exciting games.
</P>
<P>
Winding queue appeared at the children's fun corner. Not only
kids and parents but also those young at heart would like to share
the fun with pop songs stars and mime artists and participate in
the various workshops.
</P>
<P>
There were also clowns, jugglers, stilt walks, puppeteers,
balloon-twisters roving around to filling every corner with
laughter and happiness.
</P>
<P>
According to police source, the carnival attracted some 30,000
people shortly after it started. They expected more to show up
when the countdown to the new year approached.
</P>
<P>
Beside the Victoria Park where the carnival was held for the
fifth year in a row, other popular venue for welcoming the new
year include the Times Square, a shopping mall in Causeway Bay,
the pub district Lan Kwi Fong, and Tsim Sha Tsui on the southern
tip of the Kowloon Peninsular.
</P>
<P>
Under a huge TV screen on the outer wall of the Times Square,
the fifth annual New Year's Eve Apple Countdown was held. Jubilant
people filled in the nearby streets where special traffic
arrangements were made to facilitate the celebration activities.
</P>
<P>
When the clock clicked from 1997 to 1998, 15 apple light bulbs
light up one by one. People joined the countdown of the last
seconds of the old year and burst into deafening cheers when 1998
appeared right on the screen.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong people, in this way, said good-bye to 1997 and
ushered in a more prosperous new year.
</P>
<P>
Just as what John Hall said in the park, "it's my first time
working abroad and I hope I can do a good job and have a nice time
here in Hong Kong." He will work a few years here.
</P>
<P>
A shy boy caught by TV camera told of his wish, that is,
"making better in the new year."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
