<HEADLINE> OAU Chairman Conmmends Somali Peace Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Current Chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe today praised countries and organizations involved
in the peace process for their efforts leading to the signing of
reconciliation agreements between major warring groups in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said in a statement that he hoped agreements reached
after meetings in Cairo, Egypt, from November 12 to December 22,
would contribute to peace and reconciliation in war-torn Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to thank all countries, regional and international
organizations that have played a part in this process and urge
them to continue to render assistance to the process of national
reconciliation and transition to peace and stability as
necessary," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
Mugage said he was grateful for the communication sent to him
jointly by Hussein Aidid and Osman Ali Mahdi Mohammed who
co-chaired the Cairo meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two are Somalia's key warlords who have fought a bitter
civil war for years.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe noted that the decisions taken provided for the
establishment of a central authority within a federal system of
governance, an independent judiciary, a transitional government
and the convening of a national reconciliation conference.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that these and other agreements reached at the meeting
contribute to the prospect for peace, stability and
reconciliation in Somalia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
