<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Prime Minister Hails Progress in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Prime Minister Franca
Van-Dunem said here today that considerable progress has been
made in the country's peace process in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that there is no denying the fact that peace has
become reality in Angola which saw in the past year free flow of
people and goods nationwide and reunion of families broken by the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
However, the peace is still fragile, he noted, adding that to
consolidate peace in the war-torn country is one of the
government's top priorities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Faustino Muteka, the Angolan Minister of
Territorial Administration, stressed that the re-establishment of
local governments in the areas under the control of the
opposition UNITA (the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola) is an important task in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that positive progress has been made in the work in
1997. Local agovernments have been re-set up in 233 regions
controlled by the UNITA, including one provincial capital, 56
cities and 176 towns, he added.
</P>
<P>
Muteka revealed in the coming year of 1998, local governments
will also be re-established in the remaining 114 regions occupied
by the UNITA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
