<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Casts Doubt on Kenya's Election Credibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Britain Wednesday expressed
concern over the widespread reports of confusions and chaos during
Kenya's general elections and questioned the credibility of the
polls.
</P>
<P>
Tony Lloyd, junior foreign office minister, said in a statement
that "I share the widespread concern at the confusion and delays
that have accompanied the election process in Kenya, and deeply
regret the deaths and outbreaks of violence over the last few
days".
</P>
<P>
He noted that reports of irregularities in the general
elections taking place on December 29 and 30 had raised question
marks over the efficiency and credibility of the elections.
</P>
<P>
However, Britain will not make a final assessment as to whether
the elections had been free and fair before reports from
independent election observers come out.
</P>
<P>
"Britain has helped to finance a large number of independent
election observers. We shall study their reports closely before
making a final assessment as to whether the will of the Kenyan
people has been genuinely reflected in the outcome," Lloyd added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there were great confusions and chaos
during the elections because of ballot paper mix-up, unauthorized
movement of ballot boxes, violence, bribery and vote-buying by
political parties and the election was extended for a further 24
hours due to the confusions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
