<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Honors the People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair today rewarded teachers and other education workers in the
traditional honors bestowed by the Queen in the New year.
</P>
<P>
For the first time there were three knighthoods for
headteachers in state schools, and 55 awards for others involved
in education.
</P>
<P>
"There are few more important jobs than teaching. it is for
many a vocation," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of this year's awards went to ordinary members of
the public, instead of famous people, reflecting Blair's pledge to
make the honors system less political.
</P>
<P>
The singer Elton John, who sang Candle in the Wind at Diana's
funeral, received a knighthood, as does actor Michael Gambon and
former England footballer Tom Finney.
</P>
<P>
The former Conservative party chairman and final Governor of
Hong Kong, Chris Patten, became a Companion of Honor. The former
Bishop of Liverpool and England batsman, David Sheppard, was made
a life peer.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of the awards came as a result of
recommendations made by the local community. There were also a
host of honors for citizens of Commonwealth countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
