<HEADLINE> Eritrean Government on Somali Peace Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Eritrean government
has said that the recent Cairo negotiation between Somali faction
leaders ''has not brought about the desired consolidation of the
process of building consensus and reconciliation among the key
somali protagonists''.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a statement issued by the Eritrean
Foreign Ministry on Tuesday in Asmara, capital of the state of
Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean government in the statement reiterated its three
views regarding efforts aimed at promoting peace and
reconcilitation in Somalia:
</P>
<P>
Firstly, any endeavour must take into account the complexity
and sensitivity of the Somali crisis;
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the endeavours that result in the exclusion of one
part or another, or that appear to tip the delicate balance in
favour of one faction at the perceived expense of the other, will
not succeed in bringing about the desired peace and
reconciliation;
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the problem in Somalia can only be resolved by the
Somali people themselves, so no international or sub-regional
initiative can serve as a substitute to this fundamental
requirement.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on Somalis to show the necessary courage
and wisdom to bring its tragedy to an end. The Eritrean
governmenmt expressed readiness "to contribute to the
reconciliation process together with its partners in the
region'', it added.
</P>
<P>
After almost six weeks of negotiations in Cairo, Somali
faction leaders, including the two big factions of Hussein
Mohammed Aideed and Ali Mahdi Mohammed, agreed last week on
measures to end seven years of fragmentation udner rival
warlords. The agreement provides for the formation of a
presidential council, a provisional government and a constituent
assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
