<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Calls for National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- President Glafcos Clerides of
Cyprus today called for unity of the nation in 1998 to resolve the
protracted Cyprus problem and become a member of the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
In his new year message broadcast nationwide this evening,
Clerides said he hoped "that 1998 will pave the way for a
settlement of the Cyprus problem and our accession to the EU."
</P>
<P>
He expected that new initiatives for a settlement of the Cyprus
issue will be taken after the presidential election next
February in the Greek Cypriot-controlled southern part of the
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took
over the northern third to protect Turkish minorities in the wake
a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot president warned against "wrong moves" on the part
of Greek Cypriots which he said may cost the country the EU
membership and leave it in the continuing state of division.
</P>
<P>
The EU has decided to begin accession talks with Cyprus early
next year despite strong opposition from Turkey and the Turkish
Cypriots in the island.
</P>
<P>
"We all want to safeguard the future of Cypriot Hellenism in
the land of our fathers and we must all help to achieve these
goals," Clerides stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also lashed out at Turkey for "the bitter and painful
memories of the Turkish invasion and the continuing occupation of
one third of cyprus."
</P>
<P>
He said "justice for Cyprus means conditions of permanent peace
and security, progress and prosperity in the Federal Republic of
Cyprus, which will be a member of the great European family."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island in a bizonal, bicommunal
federation, but so far little tangible progress has been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
