<HEADLINE> Angola's Processing Industry Records 74 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Angola's processing industry
recorded a growth of 74 percent in the first 11 months of this
year, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The metal processing grew by 234 percent, the highest in the
whole processing industry, followed by papermaking with a growth
of 122 percent over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The food processing industry saw a growth by 111 percent,
consumer electronics 67 percent, and the beverage sector 66
percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have attributed the brisk growth in the processing industry
to the government's efforts in stablizing the
macro-economy in the past three years since the end of the civil
war.
</P>
<P>
The government's efforts in attracting private and foreign
investment has been paid off. Since 1990, the authorities have
approved 296 foreign investment projects, with contracted
investment totaling 700 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, the authorities received 25 pieces of foreign
investment applications, while more overseas businesses are still
coming.
</P>
<P>
It, however, takes Angola many more years to completely
rebuild its industry sector ruined by two decades of civil war.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the country's industrial
capacity utilization was only 35 percent at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In the coming 1998, the Angolan government is expected to take
more measures in encouraging the development of the private
sector, which will make up the loss in the state-owned
department.
</P>
<P>
The government will encourage the development of
import-replacing industries so as to save the precious fund for
the recovery of demostic production, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
