<HEADLINE> Chiluba Orders to Trasfer Prisoned Kaunda to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba here today signed a presidential order to tranfer
</P>
<P>
At a news conferrence held this morning in the State House,
Chiluba signed the order with immediate effect to transfer Kaunda
from Mukobeko Maximum Prison in Kabwe, 120 kilometers north of
the capital to house arrest in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
"Kaunda will be under the police care in his Kalundu residence
and no political activities are allowed there until all the
police investigations (into the abortive military coup last
October) are over," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He explained that he made this decision in consideration of
the former president's old age and the approaches made by some
leaders, namely former Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere, and
Zimbabwean President and Chairman of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that Zambia is an independent country and it is
not subjective to external pressures.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda is not the nation and the nation is not Kaunda, said
Chiluba, adding that "no one is above the law."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noticed that Chiluba's presidential order came
one day after Nyerere's two-day visit to Lusaka. Nyerere paid his
personal suprise visit on Monday and had a meeting with Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Nerere was entrusted by several
southern African leaders, including Nelson Mandela of South
Africa and Mugabe with a mission to press for Kaunda's immediate
release.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 73, also leader of Zambia's biggest opposition party,
the United National Independence Party, was detained on 25
December for alleged connections with the country's abotive
military last October which aimmed to overthrow Chiluba's
government.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 91 people, mostly soldiers, are detained on
presidential orders under the state of emergency declared by
Chiluba following the foiled coup. 
