<HEADLINE> European Shares End 1997 on Firm Note </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all ended the final session of this year on a firm note, with big
gains over the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The London stock market opened for only four hours today, but
closed modestly higher on the last trading day of 1997, with the
FTSE 100 index up 3.2 points at 5,135.5, a rise of 24.7 percent on
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Wall Street's hesitant start today and US
financier George Soros' warning that the international financial
system was suffering a systemic breakdown failed to dampen
European traders' high spirits.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that financial stocks fared well amid end-of-year
press tips and bid speculation.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French shares ended the year 23.44 points or 0.79
percent higher at 2,998.91 on the CAC-40 index, up 29.5 percent
over the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
The German market in Frankfurt was closed today for a market
holiday, but it also ended the year on a strong note, with the
DAX-30 index finishing 52.32 points higher at 4,249.69 on Tuesday,
a dramatic 47.1 percent rise on the start of the year. 
</P>
