<HEADLINE> Head of Nigeria's Coup Panel Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Major-General Chris Garuba has
been named chairman of the special investigation board set up by
the government to determine the role of the persons being held in
connection with the December 21 foiled coup plot.
</P>
<P>
Garuba is an officer from Nigeria's War College, the Defense
Headquarters announced today.
</P>
<P>
According to Rear Admiral Festus Porbeni, chief of defense
administration, the board, whose other members have not been
disclosed, has been divided into two to enable it to cover all
facets of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
About 15 officers have been drawn from the army, navy, air
force, police and the state security services to probe the cases
of the 12 coup suspects, including Chief of General Staff
Lieutenant-General Oladipo Diya.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations were completed before the
establishment of the special board was announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
As a result, electronic documentary materials about the
botched coup attempt have been shown to the provisional ruling
council which is the highest policy making body, the cabinet,
state administrators and a group of traditional rulers.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to be exhibited before the country's leaders
of thought and media executives.
</P>
<P>
Although investigation is going on, Porbeni said the suspects
would be allowed to have legal representatives. However, the
lawyers must come from the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
According to him, more people have been arrested in connection
with the coup bid but the government would not disclose their
names because it did not want to stigmatize those who might be
found innocent.
</P>
<P>
The defense headquarters has said the special investigation
board will have one month to finish their job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
