<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Changeable Political Climate in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba announced here today that detained former President
Kenneth Kaunda will be released but kept under house arrest in
his home in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
He said Kaunda will be restricted to his house in Lusaka under
tight security and will not be allowed to carry out political
activities until his case is determined by the courts of law.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba warned that the police will not hesitate to take him
back to prison if he does not abide by the conditions and police
orders.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement one day after former Tanzanian
President Julius Nyerere's surprise visit to Zambia, during which
he held talks with Chiluba and met with Kaunda in Mukobeko
maximum prison in the central city of Kabwe, 150 kilometers north
of Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The Post newspaper of Zambia Monday quoted diplomatic sources
as saying that southern African presidents approached Nyerere to
intercede with the Zambian government in order to secure the
release from detention of Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was reported to be spearheaded by South African
President Nelson Mandela in consultation with Ketumile Masire of
Botswana, Joachim Chissano of Mozambique, Robert Mugabe of
Zimbabwe, Sam Nujoma of Namibia and Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested last Thursday allegedly in connection with
the October 28 abortive coup. He returned home last Monday after
a Marathon overseas trip, which took him to India, South Africa,
Zimbabwe, the United States and Britain among other countries.
</P>
<P>
He went abroad on the eve of the coup to*seek international
pressure on the government.
</P>
<P>
After the abortive coup there were rumors that Kaunda would
not come back and instead would seek asylum abroad. He denied the
speculation and returned home last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some southern African countries like South Africa and others
in other part of the world expressed their concern and urged the
government to release Kaunda or he be charged.
</P>
<P>
After the arrest of Kaunda his United National Independence
Party (UNIP) and many others pulled out of the proposed
inter-party dialogue due to be held early next month.
</P>
<P>
After Zambia gained its independence in 1964 Kaunda had been
in power for successive 27 years until 1991, when he lost to
current president Chiluba in the country's first multi-party
elections.
</P>
<P>
After his defeat Kaunda resigned from politics. However, it
was not long before he returned to the political stage in 1994
and tried to regain power.
</P>
<P>
At the election year of 1996, Zambian parliament passed a
constitution amendment bill, which bars Kaunda from running for
the presidency because of his foreign parenthood.
</P>
<P>
The UNIP and some opposition parties spared no efforts to
remove the amendment but failed in the end. In protest against
the bill the UNIP boycotted the elections.
</P>
<P>
After elections the opposition parties have been continuing
their campaigns demanding an interim government and a fresh poll.
</P>
<P>
Through international mediation the ruling Movement for
Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) and opposition parties agreed to hold
inter-party dialogue in July of 1997. But the planned dialogue
didn't materialized because of the opposition parties' demands
that the repeal of the constitution amendment, formation of the
interim government and a new election be included in the agenda
of the dialogue and the government's categorical rejection.
</P>
<P>
After the dialogue was plunged into deadlock a number of
incidents happened. In mid August mysterious fires gutted cabinet
office and swallowed vendors' stalls in Lusaka, on August 23
Kaunda suffered a gunshot wound on the head in a police
clamp-down on a abortive opposition rally in Kabwe and on October
28 the coup attempt occurred.
</P>
<P>
The political situation improved early December with 31
parties working out at a preliminary meeting an agenda for the
inter-party dialogue. The agenda includes most contentious issues
like constitution, electoral process and voters' register and
fresh registration.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary meeting was hailed as a good start for a
breakthrough of the political stalemate and the achievement of
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
As presidents of the parties are going to participate in the
inter-party dialogue Kaunda was arrested. In protest against the
arrest many parties announced their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Now the government has made a compromise by transferring
Kaunda from prison to under house arrest. People doubt whether
the opposition parties will buy the move? The political
situation in the country now is at a crossroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
