<HEADLINE> S. Leone Problems Ignored by World, Says Junta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A regional minister of Sierra
Leone's military junta has accused the international community of
neglecting the problems in the country and the fuel crisis in
particular.
</P>
<P>
Lt.-Col. Francis Bottor, secretary of state for northern
region, also accused the international community of treating "the
complex situation in Sierra Leone with utter neglect," a report
reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing fuel dealers in the north of the country Tuesday,
Bottor said, "the scarcity and high cost of petroleum products is
very alarming and a remedy should be found."
</P>
<P>
The junta has been under economic sanctions and embargo
imposed by west African countries and the United Nations not long
after it seized power in a coup on May 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
Fuel and petroleum products are in the list of embargoed
goods, along with arms and other military equipment.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, fuel supplies have virtually dried
up and prices have sky-rocketed since the coup.
</P>
<P>
Petrol is now only available on the black market at 12 U.S.
Dollars a gallon, instead of the official price of three Dollars,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Diesel, he said, which is used by the majority of passenger
vehicles, has almost disappeared from the open market and now
sells at 10 Dollars a gallon, five times the official price.
</P>
<P>
"It could be disastrous if the prices are not checked," warned
Bottor, adding that many fuel products are contaminated with a
mixture of jet fuel and soft drinks to give it a reddish color.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
