<HEADLINE> Iraq Holds US Responsible for Delayed Food Delivery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq rejected U.S. allegations
that Baghdad caused delay in delivering milk powder for children,
instead blamed the U.S. for the miserable situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Iraqi Foreign Ministry said the U.S. charges
were groundless as Baghdad has always followed the measures of the U.N.
Sanctions Committee in implementing the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
He urged foreign companies having contracts with Baghdad to
adhere to the U.N. measures so as to secure early delivery of
commodities to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The contracts between Iraq and foreign companies always took
weeks before being approved because British and U.S. experts
adopted a selective policy toward them and laid down all possible
obstacles to hinder transactions, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the U.S. delegate to the U.N. committee
exacerbated the delay with objections that have nothing to do with
purchase, sale and distribution of goods, he complained.
</P>
<P>
Many contracts have been delayed or revoked during the first
and second phases of the oil-for-food deal, he said.
</P>
<P>
The deal between Iraq and the U.N., which came into effect a
year ago, allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil every six months to buy food and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said all these show how hostile the U.S.
administration has been toward Iraq and its people, accusing
Washington of harboring malicious political purposes.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was "using all illegal means of lying and cheating to
justify the heinous crimes against Iraqi people," he said,
asserting that all such policies would surely fail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
