<HEADLINE> Chinese Celebrate New Year in Diverse Ways (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- In China's sprawling territory,
people celebrated New Year's Day in merry and diverse ways.
</P>
<P>
In early morning in the Chinese capital, more than 40,000
people from all walks of life braved a chilly winter breeze to
watch the hoisting of the national flag at Tian'anmen Square while
listening to the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
Major streets in Beijing were lined with national flags and
colorful banners. Large lantern-like balloons floated in the
air. Parks, stores and entertainment places were filled with
people greeting a new festival.
</P>
<P>
In China's northeast, the 25-below-zero Celsius temperature in
Harbin did not reduce people's enthusiasm for the New Year.
</P>
<P>
On the ice-covered Songhua River in Harbin, a recently opened
amusement park was the first option of many people on New Year's
Day. The ice sculptures created a novel wonderland.
</P>
<P>
At about two in the afternoon, more than 200 people in cartoon
costumes took to the streets, a prelude to cartoon night. Children
and young people had their photos taken beside cartoon figures.
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast with the chill in Harbin, the warmth in
Guangzhou reminded people of spring. Today's parade in downtown
Guangzhou was similar to parades in urban and rural areas
throughout Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The parades, sponsored by local tourism departments, are aimed
at exhibiting the city's long history and demonstrating its
changes during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 compatriots from the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region went to Guangzhou to participate in today's
parade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Celebrate New Year in Diverse Ways (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In sunny Haikou, capital of south China's Hainan Province,
parks were also teeming.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the province maintained steady economic growth after
surmounting serious difficulties from an overheated economy. The
province's gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to
rise by 6.7 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Basking in warm sunlight, people in Xi'an greeted the first day
of the new year in the clean ancient city decorated with colorful
banners, red lanterns and balloons. Some people ascended the bell
tower, sounding the bell to greet the new year. And throngs of
people went to the downtown squares and parks.
</P>
<P>
In central China's Zhengzhou City, stilt-walking, drumming and
dancing performed by local farmers attracted crowds of people.
Along the picturesque bank of the Jinshui River, the performances
of old folk artists won applause.
</P>
<P>
On a square in the center of Shijiazhuang, more than 2,000
pigeons fluttered in the company of melodious music, sometimes
settling on the ground and playing with people. It was the first
time that pigeons were released for New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
In China's plateau city of Lhasa, a flag-raising ceremony was
held early this morning on the Potala Palace Square. Local
officials, servicemen and lamas were among 3,000 people on the
square.
</P>
<P>
Local citizens, in new clothes, went shopping or visited
relatives to extend New Year greetings.
</P>
<P>
For residents of Chongqing, the New Year's Day was the first
since Chongqing was made a municipality under the direct
administration of the central government. Sunlight managed to
break through a light mist and shine on the mountainous city.
</P>
<P>
Some 180,000 fresh flowers sent in from southern Guangzhou made
Chongqing residents fancy the flavor of spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
