<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provinces Winning War to Control Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Most of the polluters along the
once heavily polluted Huaihe River in east China's Jiangsu and
Shandong provinces have met state standards for the emission of
pollutants, local sources said today.
</P>
<P>
In Jiangsu, as much as 70 percent of the pollutants released
into the Huaihe River have been eliminated, the provincial
environmental protection agency told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Among the 385 major provincial polluters along the river, the
agency said, 230 have completed pollutants-control and passed the
state examination; 88 have finished pollution-control projects and
are awaiting for examination; and 67 have been closed either
permanently or temporarily.
</P>
<P>
Recent monitoring data shows that the water quality of the
Jiangsu section of the Huaihe River has been greatly improved,
with water quality in 82 percent of the entire section improved
over 1996 levels.
</P>
<P>
In Shandong, the Huaihe River clean-up efforts also have shown
positive results. Today the newest monitoring data shows that the
water quality in most parts of the Huaihe River in the province
have approached the Class III water quality standard, that is, it
can be used as drinking water sources.
</P>
<P>
According to the local environmental agency, during the past
two years more than 200 million yuan (some 25 million
U.S. dollars) has been spent by the province on cleaning up the
Huaihe River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
