<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Lowers Tariff Rate on Refined Oil Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
approved a uniform three percent tariff rate on imported crude oil
and refined petroleum products, the Presidential Press Office said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The office said in a press release that President Fidel Ramos
approved Wednesday the reduction of tariff rate on finished
petroleum products to three percent from the present seven
percent.
</P>
<P>
The adjustment is expected to pave the way for the creation of
a new oil deregulation law to save the country's downstream oil
industry early this year.
</P>
<P>
The country's old oil deregulation law was nullified by the
Supreme Court in November 1997 after taking effect for nine
months.
</P>
<P>
Under the old oil law, crude oil imports have a tariff rate of
three percent, while imported finished oil products have a rate of
seven percent. The rates were designed to encouraged firms to
invest in refineries in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court said forcing firms to choose between
investing huge amounts in refineries or paying higher tariffs
amounted to a restriction on free trade and violated the intention
of the law.
</P>
<P>
But the new tariff rate, to be implemented from 1998 to the
year 2000, will translate to an annual revenue loss to the
government of about 485 million pesos (12 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
