<HEADLINE> Kenyan EC Complains of Delaying Delivery of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Commission (EC)
of Kenya today complained of the delaying tactics by returning
officers, urging them to deliver their counting results of the
votes immediately.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here today, the commission said,
"Many returning officers who have completed counting are yet to
deliver the relevant certificates of results to the Electoral
Commission."
</P>
<P>
The commission directed these officers to send their counting
results to Nairobi today and those who have a valid reason should
let the commission know by telephone immediately.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial results show that over 100 of Kenya's 210
constituencies had completed their counting of votes by midday
today as the counting has been going on at a snail's pace since
the closure of the elections on December 30.
</P>
<P>
Results of around half of all the constituencies provided by
Kenya Broadcasting Corporation (KBC) and Kenya Television Network
(KTN) show that incumbent President Daniel arap Moi, National
Chairman of the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU), takes
a comfortable lead over his four leading challengers for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
However, the main opposition leaders predicted that they would
win the general elections taking place on December 29-30 and
promised to form a government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued here today, opposition
presidential candidates Mwai Kibaki, Raila Odinga and Michael
Wamalwa Kijana said, "We believe that we shall win the on-going
elections despite all odds."
</P>
<P>
Up to now, presidential candidates Joseph Martin Shikuku,
Kimani wa Nyoike and Wangari Maathai, former ministers Joseph
Kamotho and Jackson Kimeu Mulinge are among the notables who were
knocked out of parliamentary race.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Commission said yesterday that it would not
release any official results until counting is complete
throughout the country, saying that the law forbids it from
issuing partial presidential results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
