<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law Restricts Job Shifts for Workers with Commercial Secrets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Employees possessing
confidential state information or commercial secrets will not be
allowed to change jobs freely in Beijing as the result of a law
that went into effect today.
</P>
<P>
Those employees would have to compensate their employers or
face criminal penalties if they leave their working units without
authorization, divulge commercial secrets or infringe on
intellectual property rights, according to the law on the
administration of job markets.
</P>
<P>
Units that hire violators will also face a fine from 10,000 to
50,000 yuan (1,200-to-6,000 U.S. dollars). The law was recently
passed by the Beijing Municipal People's Congress, the local
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers said the law is "necessary" for the further
development of booming job markets in the city.
</P>
<P>
About 400,000 job seekers found their employers in Beijing's
job markets last year. Chinese people are enjoying more latitude
in choosing suitable careers in accordance with their skills,
abilities and wishes, said Gao Yunhou, director of the Beijing
Bureau of Personnel.
</P>
<P>
"However, legal rights and interests of employers and
intellectual property rights must be protected," he said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Beijing, the Ministry of Personnel and dozens of
provinces and cities have published regulations on the
administration of job markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firecracker-Related Injuries Hit 407 in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 407 persons were
injured in the Philippines due to firecracker use and
indiscriminate firing of guns during New Year's Eve revelry, the
Philippine News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Citing reports from various government hospitals nationwide,
the agency said 384 people were injured by firecrackers and 23
others were wounded by stray bullets from December 1 up to
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Of the 407 injured, 147 were reported from Wednesday night up
to Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Carmencita Reodica said compared to the same
period in 1996, there was a significant decline in the number of
firecracker-related injuries this year.
</P>
<P>
In December 1996, 623 firecracker-related cases were recorded
by hospitals nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Reodica attributed the decline to a campaign launched by the
health department against firecracker use, a local tradition to
greet New Year, and indiscriminate firing of guns.
</P>
<P>
Reodica also said it is necessary to ban the sale of alcoholic
beverages on New Year's Eve as most of the injured were under the
influence of liquor.
</P>
<P>
While more cases are expected to be reported, especially from
the provinces, Reodica expressed confidence that the total cases
would be much lower compared to previous years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riot, Violence Spot New Year Festival in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Riot in Strasbourg and acts of
street violence spotted the New Year festival in France, with
vehicles burnt and public properties destroyed, according to local
media reports.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-three vehicles were burnt from Wednesday night till this
morning and some bus stops and telephone cabins destroyed by rioting
youths in Strasbourg, where 500 vehicles were burnt in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 teenagers aged from 10 to 20 joined riot in all the
rough districts of the capital of Alsace Wednesday, burning dustbins
and throwing stones and cocktail molotov bombs, despite a deployment
of 400 policemen by the city police department.
</P>
<P>
A kindergarten, a cultural center and a gymnasium were also
damaged by the rioters, said police.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Luc Faivre, director of public security of Strasbourg,
said that no clash took place between police although the
anti-riot police had to disperse the rioting crowds several times.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the riot in Strasbourg was different from
those which took place in other French cities over the past several
weeks, as the former had a "socio-economic background."
</P>
<P>
Riots took place in Lyon and Fontainbleau two weeks ago after two
youths were killed by police, and the youths in Toulouse rioted
early this week after an immigrant youth was killed in a traffic
accident while driving a stolen car and being purchased by police.
</P>
<P>
Smaller scale riots and acts of street violence also took place
in Seine-Saint-Denis in the Paris region, Mulhouse in eastern
France, and Evry in Essonne south of Paris Wednesday night and this
morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
