<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan Exchange Information of Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 1 (Xinhua)-- India and Pakistan Thursday
exchanged the latest information on their respective nuclear
installations as part of an agreement on the prohibition of attack
against each other's nuclear facilities, Press Trust of India
(PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan, two rival neighbors, have exchanged through
diplomatic channels, simultaneously at New Delhi and Islamabad,
the lists of nuclear installations and facilities to be covered
under this agreement in the past 7 years.
</P>
<P>
The Indo-Pak agreement on the prohibition of attack against
each other's nuclear installations and facilities was signed on
December 21, 1988, binding the two countries to inform each other
on January 1 every year of nuclear installations and facilities to
be covered under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both the spokesmen of the two foreign offices said in their
respective Capitals that there was no change in the list from the
lists exchanged by the two countries last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
