<HEADLINE> S. Leoneans Hope for Peace in New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The new year slipped almost
unnoticed in the west African state of Sierra Leone as soldiers
heeded a warning from the military junta not to fire gunshots to
usher in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"No gunshots were heard throughout the capital and its
environs", according to reports available here today.
</P>
<P>
Civilians in the capital had braced themselves for a barrage
of gunshots which normally welcomes the new year whether under a
military or civilian government.
</P>
<P>
Gunshots fired to greet the new year in 1997 killed 10
civilians in the capital and wounded over 30.
</P>
<P>
At the main checkpoint at Jui, 13 miles east of the capital
occupied by Nigerian troops in the peacekeeping ECOMOG contingent,
the Nigerians looked very cheerful and handshaked all commuters
with a better 1998.
</P>
<P>
"We are for peace and we hope there would be no more fighting
with our Sierra Leonean brothers," one captain said.
</P>
<P>
At another checkpoint some three miles away manned by rebel
combatants of the People's Army, a commander said, "We hope the
year will usher peace among all of us, the Nigerians included."
</P>
<P>
An uneasy calm has, however, been reported in the southern
town of Bo, where Kamajor militiamen are said to be massing
around the fringes.
</P>
<P>
However, government troops are searching all vehicles entering
or leaving the town.
</P>
<P>
In Kenema in the east, six Kamajors and two soldiers were
killed on New Year's eve in a shoot out at a village 10 miles
east of Kenema.
</P>
<P>
The north is reportedly quiet and the provincial secretary
said "it is the quietest of all times." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
