<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Gulf Countries Regulate Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1997 has seen an
intensified campaign by the six Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
states to replace expatriates with locals in labor market in fight
against unemployment and other social problems.
</P>
<P>
The region currently hosts more than 10 million foreign
laborers and their families, who are active in almost all
occupations.
</P>
<P>
The swarm into the Gulf region by foreigners started from 1930s
when oil was discovered. Since then, they have been praised for
making outstanding contributions to the development of the once
poor and backward desert region.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that expatriates account for nearly 52
percent of the GCC's total population. The biggest percentage
constituted by expatriates of the local population is 80 percent
in Qatar, followed by 76 percent in the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
and 63 percent in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
They now occupy almost all the jobs in the private sector and
take a large share of the manpower in management, science and
technology sectors. They also account for a marginal share in the
working staff in governmental institutions.
</P>
<P>
Shortage of local skilled manpower, disinclination of local
people to take manual or technical jobs and low employment rate in
women of the region are believed to be the main reasons of this
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
A number of knotty social problems resulted from this
phenomenon constitute the motives for the GCC countries to launch
the campaign of Gulfization. High unemployment rate in the GCC
countries' nationals is the foremost one.
</P>
<P>
The GCC countries now have an average unemployment rate of
around 10 percent, which may grow higher in future because 50
percent of their population are under 16 years old.
</P>
<P>
In its five-year plan ending at the year 2000, Saudi Arabia
decided to create 630,000 jobs, while Kuwait needs to create
50,000 jobs in the next five years to meet the demands of newly
graduated students.
</P>
<P>
Capital outflows by expatriate workers, who remit dozens of
billions of U.S. dollars from the region to their home states
every year, also constitute a negative element to the ongoing
economic diversification process in the region.
</P>
<P>
The fear and worries about the implications of alien cultural
traditions and customs on local Islamic identity have been another
reason.
</P>
<P>
To control the foreign labor market, the GCC countries took
various measures. Firstly, they tried to restrict the employment of
foreign laborers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Gulf Countries Regulate Labor Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In this aspect, they sped up the implementation of regulations
formulated earlier to ban the hiring of expatriates by those who
are not their sponsors. If found violating these regulations, the
laborers will have their residence canceled and be deported. The
sponsors and the employers will be penalized by barring them to
recruit any new foreign laborers for six months.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia hosts more than 6 million foreign residents, more
than half of the number in the whole region. The government has
asked each private firm with 20 workers or more to make Saudis
account for at least five percent of their payroll in 1997 and to
increase the same proportion each year to be followed.
</P>
<P>
Relevant offices in Saudi Arabia were required in July to stop
issuing new work permits or extending existing ones to expatriates
in seven areas. Kuwait decided to restrict issuance of work
permits to foreigners in 13 sectors in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait also decided to replace foreigners in the public sector
with Kuwaitis at an annual rate of 10 percent and planned to make
it less attractive for the private sector to hire foreigners by
obliging it to provide them with health care and raising residency
and entry fees.
</P>
<P>
The UAE set up a committee to study ways of increasing the
number of nationals employed in the private sector although it did
not have a plan to force the sector into employing nationals.
</P>
<P>
Oman, Qatar and Bahrain have reported tangible progress in
replacing foreign laborers with their nationals as the newly
established private firms successfully managed to hire 20 to 25
percent of local people.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, repatriating illegal workers is another effort in
GCC's campaign of Gulfization process. Saudi Arabia implemented a
three-month amnesty till October 15 during which about 500,000
illegal foreign residents were deported.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 people left the UAE in a four-month grace period
ending October 31. In Kuwait, December 15 was set as the deadline
for illegal expatriates to leave in a 40-day period.
</P>
<P>
All the three countries have said the illegals who failed to
leave would, when arrested in nation-wide searches after the grace
period ended, face maximum fines of up to 10,000 U.S. dollars and
a half to two years of imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, concrete incentives to encourage private sectors to
employ local laborers have been drafted or under preparation.
</P>
<P>
The UAE intends to set up a fund to encourage the private
sector to employ nationals and a time frame is expected to be
worked out to phase in more local staff without affecting
productivity.
</P>
<P>
In joint efforts, the GCC has set up a special committee in
August to draw up joint strategy aimed at achieving demographic
balance and replacement of the expatriate labor by the national
workforce.
</P>
<P>
However, observers believe that GCC's new efforts to reduce
reliance on foreigners might continue to be blocked by the private
sector's reluctance to hire more costly local labor and a shortage
of skilled native workforce.
</P>
<P>
Local businessmen warned that they can not do their businesses
without foreign manpower.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the region's education system is not able to provide
local people with enough skills wanted by the private sector,
economists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
