<HEADLINE> Israel Opens Borders to Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel today opened its
borders to Palestinian agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The decision, in line with the 1993 Paris Agreement between the
Israelis and Palestinians, is expected to spur an increase in
exports of Palestinian agricultural products to Israel and a
subsequent drop in prices, particularly those of vegetables, in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel used to have unlimited access to the Palestinian market
although it imposed quotas on Palestinian agricultural products
sales to Israel.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, exports of Palestinian agricultural products to Israel
totalled 20 million U.S. dollars, while imports from Israel stood
at about 8.57 million dollars. The Palestinian agricultural
exports to Israel are mainly tomatoes, cucumbers and melons.
</P>
<P>
At the time of the Paris Agreement negotiations, Israeli
farmers protested the previous Labor government's decision to
expose Israeli agriculture to increased competition.
</P>
<P>
Despite the objections, the current Israeli government voted
in favor of free trade, but decided to drop the restructive trade
barriers slowly in order to help the Israeli agriculture sector
adjust to the increasing competition.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu agreed to
allocate an additional 8.6 million U.S. dollars in the 1998
state budget for agriculture investment.
</P>
<P>
The government said the extra money will help Israeli farmers
complete the transition from low to high-tech farming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
