<HEADLINE> Uganda Establishes Cholera Control Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 1 (Xinhua) --The Ugandan government has
established cholera treatment centers in 10 areas worst hit by
the epidemic, The Monitor newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The areas include Kampala, Mpigi, Luwero, Masaka and Mukono in
central Uganda and Jinja, Iganga, Bugiri, Mbale and Rukungiri
in the west, Health Minister Crispus Kiyonga was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the treatment centers, the government also keeps
its surveillance on the disease all over the country, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The main obstacle in preventing the spread of the disease is
the lack of fund and classified staff, he added.
</P>
<P>
Parliament member Wasswa Lule has attributed the outbreak partly
to poor living condition of local communities.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains in recent weeks have damaged the drainage
systems in many Ugandan cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
According to Kiyonga, the cholera outbreak has claimed 188
lives in Uganda by December 29, but Sam Okware, Chairman of the
Anti-Cholera Task Force put the toll number at nearly 300. 
</P>
