<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Huaihe River Pollution Control Gets Early Start (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- "Tick tock", as the clock hands
jointly pointing to the zero hour of Jan. 1, 1998, only one
voice could be heard at a room at China's environmental protection
headquarters: "I declare the start of the 'Midnight Operation'."
</P>
<P>
At that very moment, other voices could be heard outside
hailing the new year.
</P>
<P>
Through telephones, the concise but forceful words of Xie
Zhenhua, director of the National Environmental Protection Agency,
were delivered to more than 3,100 law-enforcement officers waiting
in the Huaihe River Valley. A large-scale, on-the-spot inspection
of the 270,000-square-kilometer area was just beginning.
</P>
<P>
As it's known to many Chinese people, lots of solemn and
stirring stories have taken place in the river valley since
ancient times. However, the anti-pollution efforts in Shandong,
Jiangsu, Anhui and Henan provinces could be the most touching in
modern history. The provinces have closed thousands of polluting
plants and spent billions of yuan during the last few years to
restore Huaihe's cleanliness and beauty.
</P>
<P>
By the zero hour today, among the 1,562 factories with daily
wastewater emissions exceeding 100 tons, 73 percent, or 1139 have
completed pollution control projects, another 190 others have been
closed, or 12 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
"The rest of the polluting factories will face closure or stop
production from midnight to seven this morning," said an official
with the agency.
</P>
<P>
About 82 percent of another 1,800 factories whose daily
emissions are below 100 tons have also completed their
anti-pollution projects. The rest will be dealt with today by
law-enforcement officers in the same way as major polluters,
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
