<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Peace Process Rocked by Belfast Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Northern Ireland peace
process has suffered another crushing blow after a man was killed
and five others wounded in a Belfast bar shooting on New Year's
Eve, local press said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that two masked gunmen, believed to be loyalist
paramilitaries, opened fire Wednesday night on drinkers in a
Catholic bar in north Belfast, the Northern Ireland capital.
</P>
<P>
This was the third killing in the province in five days. It
casts doubts on the peace process as any upsurge in sectarian
attacks is bound to place further strain on the negotiations and
could bring a violent end to the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
So far no group has claimed responsibility for the shooting.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that the masked gunmen were seeking further
revenge for the killing of the Loyalist Volunteer Force leader
Billy Wright at the Maze prison last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mo Mowlam, the Northern Ireland Secretary, had earlier issued a
New Year's message urging people to "keep the past few days in
perspective." He said peace could only come through political
talks.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, said the peace process was "shattered" by the
shooting, and called the incident a "abominable" attack.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ulster Unionist deputy leader Ken Maginnis
attacked the government after the shooting, saying the "perverse
government" had made too many concessions to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
He said his party did not excuse the attack, but pointed out
that some people now felt violence was "the only thing that pays."
</P>
</TEXT>
