<HEADLINE> Feature: Huaihe River Pollution Control Gets Early Start (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China had set a deadline of midnight Dec. 31 for all factories
in the Huaihe River Valley to meet wastewater emission
standards. Those who did not comply faced temporary or permanent
closure. Last year China closed nearly 5,000 small plants with
serious pollution.
</P>
<P>
"To date, emission of organic pollutants has been reduced by
more than 40 percent, and the water quality of Huaihe's main
stream has shown remarkable improvement," said Xie, adding that
the goal of the first-phase of Huaihe's anti-pollution war has
been met.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that pollution on some tributaries is
still serious. "Black, stinking water still flows at some places,
and that still falls far short of the target to clean up the river
by the year 2000," he said, asking the four provinces and
departments concerned under the State Council to increase their
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Twenty minutes after midnight the environmental protection
headquarters was still busy. On the huge multimedia screen on the
wall showing a map of the Huaihe River Valley with numerous dots
representing polluters and monitoring sites. Data was updated with
more information flowing in from on-site.
</P>
<P>
Phones rang one after another. With the sounding of the new
year's bell, a new page of Huaihe history had started and China
took another major step in the war of pollution control.  
</P>
</TEXT>
