<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Traffic Regulations Go into Effect in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will intensify traffic
control this year with the implementation of two new regulations
today.
</P>
<P>
The regulations give priority to public transport, enhance the
role of traffic police, establish new procedures on application
for new license plates and certificates, and ban the use of mobile
phones or pagers while driving.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, violators will face severe
penalties.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling for fines against an institution has been raised
from 1,000 yuan (120 U.S. dollars) to 30,000 yuan, and the ceiling
for individuals has been increased from 500 yuan to 1,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are more than 1.2 million vehicles
in the capital, and more than 1.9 million people have driver's
licenses. The increasing number of vehicles and limited road
facilities, along with roaming pedestrians, have resulted in
deteriorating traffic conditions, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said most of the regulations used previously had
been worked out 10 years ago and are unable to cope with current
traffic conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
