<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes Action to Huaihe Polluters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-five factories in the
Huaihe River Valley were closed this morning after a large-scale
spot inspection which proved their failure to meet state-set
emission standards. Production was temporarily halted at another
198 plants.
</P>
<P>
The inspection from midnight to seven this morning covered
1,300 factories with a daily wastewater emissions of more than 100
tons each in Henan, Anhui, Jiangsu and Shandong provinces.
</P>
<P>
On the positive side, the inspection showed that 99 percent of
the valley's factories are meeting emission standards.
</P>
<P>
"Generally speaking, the result of the inspection meets the
requirement of the State Council," said Lu Xinyuan, director of
the monitoring and environmental management department of the
National Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
The inspection showed that pollution control facilities at
eight factories' were not operating properly. Lu pledged they
would take further action for them.
</P>
<P>
The move, with the code name "Zero Hour Operation," involved
more than 3,100 law-enforcement officers. Paper strips were used
to seal the door of closed factories in some provinces.
</P>
<P>
China had demanded that all factories in the Huaihe River
Valley meet emission standards at the end of 1997 or they will
face closure or stop production.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the "Zero Hour Operation" is to implement the
central government's regulations, and to ensure the completion of
the first phase of the Huaihe River anti-pollution war, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The river valley extends 270,000 square kilometers, slightly
larger than Great Britain, and has a population of 150 million. It
is an important center of grain and energy production. The valley
has become one of the country's most seriously polluted regions
during the past decade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
