<HEADLINE> Nepal Cheers First Day of Tourism Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 1 (Xinhua) -- With food and fun festival,
carnival parade, fireworks and drum presentation on the New Year
day, the Himalayan kingdom of Nepal cheered the first day of the
Visit Nepal Year' 1998 (VNY'98).
</P>
<P>
At noon, Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa led the carnival
parade round the downtown area of the capital city before
returning to the King's Way in front of the Royal Palace.
</P>
<P>
As the government has announced Thursday a public holiday to
mark the first day of the VNY'98, spectators thronged about the
streets.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra, government officials and foreign guests attended
the nearly two-and-a-half-hour inaugural ceremony held near a
specially-built gate at the King's Way.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, representatives from other parts of the
country and from different walks of life filed through the gate.
Dozens of floats displayed the country's traditional culture.
</P>
<P>
Fireworks and drum presentation, which began from 6 PM, added
to the attraction of the inaugural day.
</P>
<P>
The VNY'98 aims to create public awareness toward tourism,
develop infrastructure, standardize services, increase the tourist
arrivals to 500,000 from an average of 300,000 in the past years.
</P>
<P>
The VNY'98 was launched by the government in April 1996. As
King Birendra noted in his New Year message, "Tourism has come to
occupy an important place in our economy... However, given the
full potential for tourism, much more remains to be done."
</P>
