<HEADLINE> New Year's Day Celebrated in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- People in the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China held various
celebrations Thursday to mark the New Year's Day, the first after
Hong Kong's return to the motherland on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Chinese General Chamber of Commerce (CGCC) held a
reception to celebrate the New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the reception, CGCC Chairman Tsang Hin Chi said that
Hong Kong had run as usual in the fields of politics, economy and
social affairs in the past six months after the handover.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong people and foreign investors are becoming more
and more confident in the SAR's future, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
Tsang encouraged members of the CGCC to continue to fully
support the operation of the SAR government and make efforts for
the bright future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On the New Year's Day, the Provisional Regional Council
organized carnivals at seven venues for members of the public.
</P>
<P>
At the Dance Carnival at the Tai Po Sports Ground, the main
attraction was a dragon dance by more than 1,000 dancers.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the Martial Arts Carnival at Tin Shui Wai
Sports Ground was trees displaying New Year messages from
residents.
</P>
<P>
Other programs include performances by Guangdong and Jiangsu
provincial badminton teams, the Guangdong Dance School, the
Guangdong Wushu (martial arts) Team, the Hong Kong Dance
Federation and the Hong Kong Wushu Union.
</P>
<P>
On the New Year's eve, thousands of Hong Kong people
participated in a Family Fun Carnival at Victoria Park, Causeway
Bay.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Provisional Urban Council (PUC), the outdoor
party provided four hours of non-stop entertainment for all age
groups.
</P>
<P>
The six football pitches of the park were decorated as a
spectacular carnival, with glamorous setting including the music
stage, dance and fringe stage, big top disco, nostalgic ballroom
dance tent and the children's fun corner.
</P>
<P>
There were also clowns, jugglers, stilt walks, puppeteers,
balloon-twisters roving around to filling every corner with
laughter and happiness.
</P>
<P>
Beside the Victoria Park where the carnival was held for the
fifth year in a row, other popular venues for welcoming the new
year include the Times Square, a shopping mall in Causeway Bay,
the pub district Lan Kwi Fong, and Tsim Sha Tsui on the southern
tip of the Kowloon Peninsular.  
</P>
</TEXT>
