<HEADLINE> Israel: Palestinian Prisoner Mistreated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli General Security
Service (GSS) has admitted that it had used methods such as
depriving a Palestinian prisoner of sleep in order to elicit
information to prevent terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
This came in a report by the GSS to the High Court of Justice
in response to a petition lodged by the Public Committee Against
Torture in Israel (PCATI) on behalf of a Bir Zeit University
student, Fuad Kuran, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kuran, who is under intensive interrogation had been deprived
of sleep for a long time, said the GSS.
</P>
<P>
The petition asked the GSS to stop torturing Kuran and allow
him to see a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
Kuran, arrested on December 10, is the brother-in-law of Adel
Awadallah, who is suspected to have masterminded at least two
suicide bombing attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
In what was described as a precedent-setting decision, the
High Court of Justice on Sunday ordered the GSS to provide the
court with its detailed interrogation log book within 48 hours,
including the rationale for the methods used.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the State Attorney's Office said that one section
of the log book would have to remain secret for reasons of state
security. But it revealed part of its report.
</P>
<P>
"The petitioner (suspect) is not permitted to sleep as he
wishes, is interrogated for different periods of time or is in a
state of waiting for interrogation without enjoying the period
meant for sleep," the report reads.
</P>
<P>
"However, he is sent to his cell for sleep when the needs of
the interrogation make this possible," said the report.
</P>
<P>
Court President Aharon Barak, who heads the three-member panel
hearing the petition, said on Wednesday that he could not convene
another hearing until all the material of the report had been
studied.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem District Court on Wednesday remanded Kuran for
a further eight days and ruled that he would still not be able
to meet a lawyer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
