<HEADLINE> Repatriation of Bangladeshi Tribal Refugees Resumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Repatriation of Bangladesh's
remaining 35,000 tribal refugees from the Indian state of Tripura
resumed Thursday after a 25-day break, the independent United News
of Bangladesh reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth phase of repatriation process from
Kathalchharl refuge camp in Tripura State.
</P>
<P>
Nine hundred and forty-one refugees from 185 tribal families
returned home from Kathalchharl camp through the Dakbanglaghat
frontier point on the first day of the phase.
</P>
<P>
Receiving the refugees Thursday morning were Refugee Affairs
Task Force Committee Chairman Kalparanjan Chakma and Chittagong
Division Commissioner Sakhawat Hossain Khan.
</P>
<P>
All preparations have been taken to receive the refugees at the
frontier and rehabilitate them in their respective homesteads in
the three hill districts.
</P>
<P>
In the past phases, about 20,000 tribal refugees have so far
returned home from India.
</P>
<P>
Many tribal people sought shelters in India in 1962 after the
Kaptai Hydro-electric dam flooded 350 square miles (906.5 square
kilometers) of their most fertile land and displaced over 100,000
people from their homes. From then on, the tribals had been waging
struggle for autonomous rights.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's refusal in 1973 to restore the area's historic
special status led to more than 20 years' guerrilla wars between
the government and the tribals, which were ended by the signing of
a peace agreement between them on Chittagong Hill Tracts early
last month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
