<HEADLINE> Guangxi's GDP Up 9 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region topped 200 billion yuan in gross domestic
product (GDP) last year,
</P>
<P>
That figure represents a rise of 9 percent over the previous
year, sources at the region's statistics bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The economic achievements were mainly attributed to the rapid
development of semitropical agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the agricultural output increased 11 percent
over the 1996 figure. With the regional government's emphasis on
agriculture, the region produced a bumper crop of grain.
</P>
<P>
The region produced 16.6 billion kilograms of grain last year,
up 3.4 percent over 1996. And the total output of subtropical
fruit -- such as longans, litchi, bananas and pineapples -- was
3.18 million tons, three times more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The cane sugar output topped 2.6 million tons, ranking first in
the country for five consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index increased one percentage point last
year, almost equal to 1996. As a result, 1.2 million farmers in
the region escaped poverty last year.
</P>
<P>
To open wider to the outside world, the region paid close
attention to infrastructure construction. The region built the
Guilin-Beihai expressway, and expanded Guilin International and
Nanning airports. The ports of Fangcheng, Qinzhou and Beihai now
can handle more than 10 million tons of cargo a year.
</P>
<P>
The region topped three billion U.S. dollars in imports and
exports, up 6 percent over 1996, and utilized more than one
billion U.S. dollars in foreign investment last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
