<HEADLINE> Crisis Looming for Shippers in Third World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A crisis could be looming in
third world shipping industry as most seafarers are finding it
difficult to be employed in world class vessels, the East African
Standard newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
This follows the imposition of new rules by International
Maritime Organization (IMO) on the standards of training that
must be met by all seafarers, said the report.
</P>
<P>
IMO introduced standards in February last year for training
certification and watch-keeping, known as STCW, under which sea
worker must undergo from internationally recognized training
institutions and get a certificate that meets the requirements of
the STCW.
</P>
<P>
The new move was aimed at ensuring that those working in the
shipping industry are highly qualified and could serve
effectively.
</P>
<P>
However, most seafarers in the developing countries get
haphazardly "trained" while they go about their daily duties.
</P>
<P>
Most third world states have not been putting emphasis on
training of seafarers and, therefore, leaving a majority who
fails to get formal training and would find themselves
unemployable one day, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, with the worldwide liberalization of the shipping
industry, stiff competition has been witnessed and more and more
shipping merchants now prefer quality service, making new
challenges to the third world.
</P>
<P>
The report urged the developing countries with ports to make
efforts to train qualified seafarers so as to meet increasing
challenges in the fields of both technology and service of the
maritime industry, otherwise they will be in the mire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
