<HEADLINE> OAU Chairman: Most Africa's Problems Resolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Organization of
African Unity and Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said
remaining military rules in Africa should move away to allow
civilian rule in the new year.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told a New Year's eve party he hosted in Harare that
1998 should see most of Africa's political turmoil being resolved
saying more effort would be put in to boost the fragile peace
processes.
</P>
<P>
Painting a hopeful picture for the resolution of conflicts
bedevilling the world's poorest continent, he said his
organization supported most of the liberation movements making
legitimate demands.
</P>
<P>
"There are still other places where there are military
dictatorships and we hope these areas will go to civilian rule,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Africa's most populous nation of Nigeria is still under the
military rule of Sani Abacha who has promised however, that
elections to bring in a civilian government would be held in
October 1998.
</P>
<P>
"We are hoping that the situation in Somalia is about to get
its solution as the war lords have now come together," said
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Another trouble spot of Africa is neighbouring Angola where
the Lusaka protocol signed between Eduardo Dos Santos and Jonas
Savimbi is threatened by the latter's non-compliance with
provisions of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi who has apparently ignored some sections of the
protocol is expected this year to make major compromises that
will see Angola finally get over its civil war that tore the
southern African country for years and caused the death of
thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
On Saharawi, a nation seeking autonomy from the rule of
Morocco, Mugabe said he was hopeful that a referendum to be held
later this year would grant the Saharawis their desired goal.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see them (Saharawi) emerge as an independent state
and we hope Sudan will also get corrected," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking strongly against continued sanctions on Libya by the
international community, Mugabe said it was time that the air
embargo was lifted.
</P>
<P>
Libya ostracized for its refusal to have its nationals tried
in Scotland for the Lockerbie downing of an plane, has promised
that it would release the suspects as long as the trial was held
in a neutral country like Switzerland, though presided over by
Scottish officials.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also called for renewed dialogue between the Palestine
Liberation Organisation (PLO) and the Israeli government of
Benjamin Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
