<HEADLINE> S. Africa/Zimbabwe Trade Imbalance Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's trade imbalance with
neighbouring South Africa continues to increase and the trend is
not expected to change unless Harare introduces effective export
incentives, the Zimbabwe News Agency, Ziana, reported today.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Ziana, President of the Confederation of
Zimbabwe Industries (CZI) Jonee Blanchfield said the imbalance
threatened local industry as the market would be choked by South
African imports.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we can do something about the trade imbalance we are
going to see a collapse of business even more in this country,"
said Blanchfield.
</P>
<P>
Of Zimbabwe total import bill, nearly 40 percent is South
African exports.
</P>
<P>
While Pretoria exported goods worth more than 10.8 billion
Zimbabwean Dollars to Harare, it imported two billion Zimbabwe
dollars worth of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
Currently one U.S. Dollar equals to 17 Zimbabwean Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Blanchfield, a staunch critic of the delay in reviewing the
1964 trade agreement which expired in 1992, has been castigated
by South African President Nelson Mandela for her previous
scathing comments which he said would not help the situation.
</P>
<P>
But Blanchfield prefers the issue to be resolved once and for
all and erase the animosity currently prevailing between the two
countries' business communities.
</P>
<P>
"Our trade imbalance with South Africa should be objectively
resolved, we either speed up the trade agreements or put in some
form of counter measures because the imbalance is widening and it
is denting our cash crisis," she said.
</P>
<P>
She added Zimbabwe should in the new year concentrate on
improving its image to attract potential investors.
</P>
<P>
On devaluation of the Zimbabwean Dollar against major
currencies in recent weeks, she said reduction of the national
budget deficit was the only way out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
