<HEADLINE> Israel Greets New Year Without State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel greeted the year 1998
today without a state budget, as the government failed to gain
sufficient support for its draft budget proposal overnight.
</P>
<P>
The inner bickering and bargaining within the coalition
continued into midnight Wednesday, but the main dispute between
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Foreign Minister David Levy
remained unsettled.
</P>
<P>
Overnight negotiations held between Levy and Netanyahu's office
ended without an agreement. Both Levy and Netanyahu returned
to their homes in disappointment. It is not clear if Levy
will return from his home in Beit Shean in the West Bank
to the Knesset (Parliament) to attend further debate over the
budget.
</P>
<P>
Levy accused Netanyahu for failing to honor his promise made to
Levy's Gesher's party that the budget incorporates more funds for
control of deficit in health sector and the development of towns.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Gesher, another coalition party United Torah
Judaism and several lawmakers of the ruling Likud party also
remained opposed to the budget of 207 billion shekels (59.1
billion U.S. dollars), which includes a 2.6 billion-shekel
expenditure cut.
</P>
<P>
The religious United Torah Judaism is fighting for allocation
of more funds to offer cheap housing for the religious
students.
</P>
<P>
And three hardline Likud lawmakers Zeev Begin, Uzi Landau and
Rubi Rivlin conditioned their support to the budget on
Netanyahu's promise to limit the scope of planned troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The government, now boasting 66 seats, needs at least 61 votes
of the 120-seat Knesset to get the budget passed. Without the
support of the Gesher, with five seats, and the United Torah
Judaism, with four seats, and the three Likud lawmakers, the
government would fall if it puts the budget proposal for voting
now.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who has long been at odds with Netanyahu over
political and economic policies, is once again reportedly
considering resignation and working for early elections. Some
coalition lawmakers have already called for holding early
elections in order to stop what they called the "blackmailing"
of the government by small parties.
</P>
<P>
Gesher lawmaker David Magen said he believed it might be
possible to find the 80 votes needed to oust Netanyahu without
dissolving the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The opposition camp, meanwhile, stepped up its offensive
against the government over the budget crisis. The leading
opposition Labor party leader Ehud Barak said Wednesday night
that the government's failure to pass the budget "is a sign
of the total collapse of the Netanyahu government."
</P>
<P>
Still, Finance Minister Ya'acov Neeman said that he was
confident that the budget would be finally approved imminently
with its original framework remaining roughly intact.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset is to continue voting on the economic arrangement
bills accompanying the budget today. And the government is
expected to present its draft budget to the Knesset plenum for
voting Friday morning if Netanyahu solves all the disputes with
his coalition and party colleagues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
