<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis' Income Sees First Drop Since 1985 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel's per capita
disposable income dropped by 2 percent in 1997 after continuous
increases since 1985, today's The Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics as
saying that the decline was coincident with the slowdown of
Israel's economy this year. And it was also affected by the
increase in payments to the National Insurance Institute and
to income tax.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released by the bureau Wednesday,
Israel's Gross Domestic Product increased by only 2 percent in
1997, compared with 4.5 percent in 1996 and 7 percent in 1995 and
1994.
</P>
<P>
And Israel's per capita pre-tax income remained unchanged in
1997 at 58,000 shekels (about 17,000 U.S. dollars), compared to a
2 percent increase in 1996, and 4 percent in both 1995 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that Israel's per capita income, as compared
with other Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development
(OECE) countries, is similar to income in Finland and New Zealand,
and higher than in Spain and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's consumer spending also slowed in the past
year, growing by less than 1 percent, compared with an increase of
3 percent in 1996 and 5 to 6 percent increase from 1993 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, consumption of durable goods in Israel dropped by
2 percent per capita, including a 19 percent decline in new
car purchases. And expenditure on food dropped by 2 percent
after continuous increases from 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
