<HEADLINE> China Opens Embassy in S. Africa (Detailed) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen opened China's embassy in South
Africa here today.
</P>
<P>
Under a joint communique signed by Qian and South African
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo Tuesday, the two countries have
established diplomatic relations at ambassadorial level as from
today.
</P>
<P>
China's national flag was raised in the yard of the embassy,
and the national anthem, March of the Volunteers, was played
while hundreds of people watched with emotion.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the Chinese government, I formally declare the
Embassy of the People's Republic of China in South Africa opens,"
Qian said at the ceremony presided over by Wang Xuexian, the
first Chinese ambassador to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Qian unveiled a plaque bearing the name "Embassy of the
People's Republic of China" among a warm applause.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier said in a brief speech that the embassy would
contribute to the enhancement of understanding and traditional
friendship between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Nzo, who was also present at the ceremony, said: "On this
first day of the establishment of diplomatic relations, the
unveiling of the plaque marks a historic occasion in our
bilateral relations."
</P>
<P>
"In the years to come, this name plaque will remind us of the
first step in a journey of a thousand miles that was started here
today -- to quote a famous Chinese proverb."
</P>
<P>
"From now on, this embassy will take on an even more important
role as we seek to develop not only our bilateral relations to
their fullest potential, but also to coordinate our efforts to
pursue the interests of the developing countries in the
international political and economic system."
</P>
<P>
Deputy minister of China's Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, Shi Guangsheng, assistant foreign minister, Ji
Peiding, also attended the ceremony held at 972 Pretorius Street,
Acadia, Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived in South Africa last Friday, is due to
return home later today.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day stay in South Africa, he also met
President Nelson Mandela, National Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala
and held talks with Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
