<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Faces Difficult New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania faces a tough
new year after the country started with drought and ended with
floods in 1997, President Benjamin Mkapa has said.
</P>
<P>
In his new year message broadcast to the nation last night,
Mkapa said 1998 is likely to be difficult for all Tanzanians even
if weather turns better.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said donors have pledged to provide Tanzania with 68,640
tons of food in response to the government's appeal last
September. The food relief supplies are expected to arrive in the
country from January 15 and will be distributed to needy areas.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said last September the country would face a shortage of
916,000 tons of food during the 1997/1998 season.
</P>
<P>
To ease food shortage, the government last year waived taxes
on imports of maize in a bid to encourage private businessmen to
import food. However, the response was cold.
</P>
<P>
By yesterday 53,300 tons of food, including 20,000 tons of
maize had been imported by private businessmen, merely 13 percent
of the needed amount.
</P>
<P>
The food situation was worsened by floods starting from early
December, which have paralyzed a number of roads, bridges and the
Central railway. Food and other necessities are difficult to
reach the market, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological departments predicted that the floods linked to
El Nino weather phenomenon will last until April.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the weather is favorable we should expect 1998 to be
a difficult year, as much damage has been done," he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic losses have yet to be known as floods have blocked
traffic or cut off communication to a number of areas. But
Tanzanian Prime Minister told reporters yesterday that the floods
have killed 38 people and left tens of thousands of people
homeless.
</P>
<P>
The president also said between January and September last
year, 1,249 people died and 10,195 were injured in 11,420 road
and railway accidents.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 1,984 people on Tanzanian mainland and 140 others
in Zanzibar isles died of cholera last year. A total of 36,182
people contracted the disease in 1997, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
