<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Decries Post-Election Atrocities in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force in Liberia known as ECOMOG has expressed deep concern about
what it called dangerous trends characterizing the post-election
era in that country, the Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG chief of staff Brig.-gen. Adbul One Mohammed, who
voiced the feeling Wednesday, warned that unless the trends were
checked by the political leadership of that country, they were
capable of generating fresh bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
The general listed a number of things as some of the bad
developments that could re-ignite the conflict.
</P>
<P>
They include alleged abduction and assassination of known
political figures and prominent politicians; re-enlistment of
soldiers who have been identified with the seven-year fratricidal
war in the country and indiscriminate arrests of journalists on
flimsy excuses.
</P>
<P>
But he did not mention Nay Culprit, saying his warning was
part of the duty ECOMOG owed the people of Liberia before it
finally moves out of the country next month.
</P>
<P>
Early last month, a former ally of President Charles Taylor,
Sam Dokie was abducted and found dead three days later.
</P>
<P>
Dokie allied to Taylor at the beginning of his rebel struggle
against the former government. He later fell out with Taylor, the
then leader of a major warring faction, National Patriotic Front
of Liberia (NPFL), complaining that Taylor did not want the war
to end.
</P>
<P>
Thereafter, a journalist, who reportedly went to cover the
burial of Dokie, was also abducted at Gbarnga, the former
headquarters of NPFL where he had gone to interview certain
personalities.
</P>
<P>
"The problems would not help in bringing peace to the country.
But since we are still on the ground, we will continue to appeal
to them to do the right thing," the ECOMOG chief said.
</P>
<P>
As several ECOMOG soldiers lost their lives and billions of
U.S. Dollars were spent during the peacekeeping operations, the
general said "we do not want to see what will bring about
uprising in the country so as not to defeat the purpose of our
being here."
</P>
<P>
"If we leave this country, we can't imagine what will happen
to them," he said, adding that this concern is also expressed by
the international community.
</P>
<P>
"The entire international community is watching the
development with grave concern," he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
