<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Chapter in China-South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- With the opening of the
Chinese Embassy in South Africa in Pretoria today, the two
developing countries, influential in Asia and Africa
respectively, finally completed the process of the normalization
of relations, opening a brand-new chapter for bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen, who
opened the embassy, said the diplomatic facility will make
contributions to the enhancement of understanding and traditional
friendship between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said: "The name
plaque (of the embassy) will remind us of the first step in a
journey of a thousand miles that was started today."
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a joint communique Tuesday to
establish diplomatic relations as from today.
</P>
<P>
Together with the joint communique signed by Qian and Nzo, the
two countries also signed agreements on diplomatic representation
in each other's countries, investment protection and aviation.
</P>
<P>
During meetings with Qian, South African leaders stressed that
China plays an important role in international affairs and that
the establishment of diplomatic relations with China is in the
interests of both peoples.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela declared in November
1996 that his country would sever ties with Taiwan and recognize
the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said after talks with Qian on Monday that China is the
most populous nation in the world and a permanent member of the
United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"It is in the interests of South Africa to have relations with
such a country. They are also one of the fastest growing economic
giants in the world and therefore it is in the interests of both
countries to have diplomatic relations."
</P>
<P>
Nzo told a reception in honor of Qian on Tuesday evening that
the establishment of diplomatic relations with China would have
been a "foregone conclusion a long time ago" if it had not been
for the apartheid system.
</P>
<P>
"It would have been totally untenable that a situation should
continue to exist where one of the leading countries in Africa
does not have formal relations with one of the leading countries
in Asia and the world."
</P>
<P>
"The continuation of such a situation would have been
inconsistent with decisions taken by international bodies such as
the UN and the OAU (Organization of African Unity), international
law and the state practice followed by the overwhelming majority
of countries," Nzo said in a cordial speech.
</P>
<P>
He said earlier that the establishment of formal relations
with China is an important achievement of diplomacy of the
African National Congress and the South African government.
</P>
<P>
National Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala said in a meeting with
Qian on Sunday that after the normalization of relations, the two
countries could forge better cooperation in bilateral relations
and in international politics. She described Qian's visit and the
establishment of diplomatic relations as an important milestone
in the history of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Exchanges and cooperation between China and South Africa dated
back to long time ago. In not more than a year after the founding
of the People's Republic of China in 1949, Chinese leader Mao
Zedong sent a message to liberation organizations in Transvaal to
express China's support to their just course against apartheid.
Ever since then friendship was established between South Africa's
major black liberation groups and China.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has said repeatedly that the Chinese government and
its people have always been supportive to South Africans during
apartheid years.
</P>
<P>
When explaining to reporters the reason for the establishment
of diplomatic relations with China on Tuesday, Nzo said
relationship with China was long-standing and that the diplomatic
recognition was a continuation of friendship between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He told the Tuesday reception that the move was a "natural
outcome" of contacts of more than 300 years.
</P>
<P>
Both Qian and South African leaders believe that the
establishment of formal ties will give fresh impetus to trade
relations since both countries face the common task of developing
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Recent years have witnessed rapid growth in bilateral trade.
Trade volume jumped to 1.35 billion U.S. dollars from merely 14
million dollars in 1991. It is expected to exceed 1.6 billion
dollars this year, not counting South Africa's trade of 1.4
billion dollars with China's Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region.
</P>
<P>
Two figures combined, China is South Africa's sixth largest
trading partner in the world.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is now China's biggest trading partner in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Strong trade links will lay a firm foundation for future
cooperation, Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
In view of the traditional friendship, strong trade links and
each other's important role in international and regional
affairs, South African leaders have indicated that the two
countries should enhance cooperation on international issues.
</P>
<P>
Nzo said Tuesday that South Africa and China, both developing
countries, share many similar ideals and objectives, such as the
equality of every member of the international community and the
safeguarding of the interests of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, South Africa, as a non-aligned country
pursuing an independent foreign policy, is looking forward to
forging a strategic partnership with China for the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Both sides believe that with the normalization of relations, a
new era of bilateral relations and cooperation in various fields
is unfolding before the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
