<HEADLINE> Laid-off Workers Get Re-employment Help in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Statistics from the Guangdong
Provincial Labor Department shows that 310,000 laid-off workers
and 130,000 jobless people were re-employed from January through
September last year in this southern province of China.
</P>
<P>
With re-employment rate dramatically rising to 62 percent,
unemployment rate was brought down further to 2.3 percent in the
province, according to an official in charge of re-employment in
the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong set up a provincial re-employment fund in
October. Cities such as Guangzhou, Zhuhai, Shantou, and Zhongshan
also have their own funds to aid the jobless.
</P>
<P>
Statistics shows that 180,000 laid-off workers and jobless
people attended training in the first half of 1997, accounting for
35 percent of those out of work. The re-employment rate of the
trainees reached 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The workers laid-off by state enterprises are mostly from
traditional industries. Their cultural and technical qualities
usually fall short of the demands of newly emerging industries,
high-technology companies and such high-grade service sectors as
information and finance, a provincial official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
