<HEADLINE> Coastal, Inland Areas Seek Common Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Enterprises in China's developed
coastal areas have provided funds and technologies for the
less-prosperous central and western areas as a way of common
development.
</P>
<P>
On a mutually beneficial basis, the central and western areas
have provided energy and raw materials in large amounts in their
cooperation with the coastal regions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, enterprises in the coastal areas have established
stable economic ties with and helped promote economic
restructuring of their counterparts in the central and western
areas.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the proportion of primary industry has
dropped 0.4 percent in the national economy and 0.8 percent in the
secondary industry in the central and western areas this year,
while the proportion in the service sector has increased 1.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi, an undeveloped province in north China, has introduced
more than 4,000 items of new technologies from the coastal areas
in the past three years, and upgraded its light industry, textile
and clothing sectors.
</P>
<P>
The province, a leading coal producer in the country,
transports more than 200 million tons of coal to 26 provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions every year. The raw coal
produced in the province accounts for one-fourth of the country's
total. And the province effectively utilized the earnings from
coal in 280 items of technological innovations.
</P>
<P>
As the country's largest industrial and financial center,
Shanghai has invested 3.5 billion yuan (437.5 million
U.S. dollars) in the fields of education, culture and public
health in the central and western areas, including 200 million
yuan of free economic aid.
</P>
<P>
In the last three years, the city has committed 100 million
yuan to the building of a hydropower station and a hospital in
southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shanghai has sent 150 groups of outstanding
professional technicians to the region, as well as Yunnan and
Guizhou provinces, and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, and
launched more than 1,500 anti-poverty projects there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
