<HEADLINE> U.S. Top Judge Criticizes Senate for Inaction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist warned that the "quality of justice" of the country
may be threatened by the Senate's delay in acting on scores of
President Bill Clinton's judicial nominees.
</P>
<P>
In his year-end report, the nation's top-ranking judge pointed
a finger of blame at the Senate for "serious delays in the
appointment process."
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist said that 82 of 846 federal judgeships remain vacant,
and 26 of those vacancies have existed for 18 months or longer.
</P>
<P>
He said such a high level of vacancies cannot continue "without
eroding the quality of justice that traditionally has been
associated with the federal judiciary."
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist said both the president, who nominates judicial
candidates, and the Senate, which must confirm them, "bear some of
the responsibility" for the judicial crunch. But he was more
critical of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
"Some current nominees have been waiting a considerable time
for a Senate Judiciary Committee vote or a final floor vote,"
Rehnquist said. "The Senate confirmed only 17 judges in 1996 and
36 in 1997, well under the 101 judges it confirmed in 1994."
</P>
<P>
In September, President Clinton accused Senate Republicans of
putting politics above justice, but Senator Orrin Hatch, the
Republican who chairs the Judiciary Committee, said Clinton's
criticism was unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist's report said federal courts' workloads continue to
grow, due in part to federal laws that have expanded federal
jurisdiction over crimes involving drugs and firearms.
</P>
<P>
"If federal jurisdiction remains at its current level -- or,
worse, increases -- judicial vacancies will aggravate the problem
of too few judges and too much work," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist also criticized President Clinton's failure to name
new members of the Sentencing Commission, which conducts
sentencing-related research and issues guidelines on punishment
for federal crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
