<HEADLINE> U.S. Balloonist Launches Third Around World Try </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Adventurer Steve Fossett
launched his "Solo Spirit" balloon into sky from a sports stadium
on Wednesday night in his third try for a nonstop balloon trip
around the world.
</P>
<P>
Fossett's balloon lifted off flawlessly at 5:04 p.m. CST (2304
GMT) from Busch Stadium in downtown St. Louis, local media reports
said.
</P>
<P>
If all goes as planned, Fossett will sail on a favorable upper
air jet stream that would push his balloon over the Atlantic Ocean
on a trip that would last about 15 days if successful.
</P>
<P>
Fossett planned to balloon over northeast England, Ukraine,
Russia, Kazakhstan, China, southern Japan and over the Pacific to
British Columbia with a landing northeast of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
"We have prepared properly and we have a very realistic
chance," the 53-year-old stock options broker was quoted as saying
prior to departure.
</P>
<P>
Air traffic at Lambert Field in St. Louis was diverted around
the stadium to give Fossett clear sailing.
</P>
<P>
Fossett has already set a record in time and distance as he
ballooned last January with a six-day, 16,000-kilometer trip from
St. Louis to India.
</P>
<P>
Because of shortage of fuel to cover the whole journey, Fossett
had to touch the land near Sultanpur, India in the last try.
</P>
<P>
This time he is carrying 50 percent more fuel and his balloon
is 28 percent larger at 350,000 cubic feet (9,800 cubic meters).
He will burn an ethane and propane fuel mixture to heat air
surrounding the helium encapsulated in the balloon and thus
control his altitude.
</P>
<P>
Fossett also has an oxygen mask and a separate heating system
for the unpressurized capsule to combat upper altitude
temperatures that drop as low as as minus 45.4 degrees Celsius.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Calls on EU to Renew Trade Privileges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav government Wednesday
called on the European Union (EU) to reconsider its decision of
terminating trade privileges extended to the southeastern European
nation.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported that Prime Minister
Radoje Kontic hosted a meeting Wednesday in response to the EU's
refusal.
</P>
<P>
The government said that the EU move shows that the bloc is
adopting double standard in handling international affairs.
</P>
<P>
The EU decision, which is nothing but discrimination against
the country, will set back the country's fledging economic reform
and hurt the development of the Southeastern Europe as a whole,
the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
An EU spokesman said on Tuesday that the bloc has decided not
to renew trade privileges to Yugoslavia next year because of human
rights and other issues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trade preferences for Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia
are expected to be renewed for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The EU trade benefits included offering Yugoslavia duty-free
access to the EU and eliminating restrictions on imports of
industrial products.
</P>
<P>
The EU move is another blow to the country, which was hit by
years of U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed a trade embargo on Belgrade in 1992
for its alleged role in the Bosnian war, but lifted it in October
1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the so-called outer wall of the sanction was left in
place, which bans the country from access to international
financial organizations and foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the United States decided to extend
financial sanctions against Yugoslavia for another year as part of
the "outer wall" sanction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
