<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Gives Special Treatment to Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Romania will grant special
treatment to overseas investors in an effort to attract more
foreign capital, under an urgent decree put into effect Wednesday
by the government.
</P>
<P>
The decree, "On Encouraging Direct Investment," says foreigners
can make investments in every economic field and by any forms
permitted by law.
</P>
<P>
It also says investors will enjoy more preferential policies no
matter what their nationalities, whether or not they reside in
Romania and regardless of the amount of their investments.
</P>
<P>
It stipulates that imports of machine equipment are free of
customs tariffs, and that investors can reduce profit taxes by
subtracting 20 percent of a machine's purchase costs or its
depreciation charges from before-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
The favorable policy won't be altered within five years, the
order says.
</P>
<P>
Romania passed a law on foreign capital in April of 1991, and
has since amended it several times.
</P>
<P>
Romania attracted about 150 million U.S. dollars in overseas
capital in 1997, the largest amount in recent years.
</P>
<P>
But compared with Poland, Hungary and some other eastern and
central European countries, Romania still needs to strengthen
efforts to attract more capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
