<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Appoint Commission on Missing Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has given an assurance to appoint an independent
commission to inquire into the fate of over 600 persons who have
gone missing after they were arrested in the Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The assurance was made when the president met with a delegation
of the Guardian Association, which represents the missing people
who had been arrested by the security forces in the peninsula, The
Island newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There have been 854 complaints about missing persons since
government troops took over the peninsula from rebel hands in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The president said 150 of them had been traced. About 26 had
been released on bail and nine had been confirmed dead.
</P>
<P>
The whereabouts of the remainders are not known.
</P>
<P>
The president promised that similar incidents should not take
place again. She said she will take action against those
responsible for the disappearances of people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
