<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Economic Growth Forecast at 0.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic growth for
1997 could be only 0.3 percent, compared with 6.4 percent posted
in 1996, according to the National Economic and Social Development
Board, the country's national planning agency.
</P>
<P>
The board also forecast that the economy would grow by just 0.4
percentage points to 0.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of the board Wednesday spent five hours
reporting to the cabinet on the country's economic performance of
1997 and making policy suggestions for 1998, according to the
Bangkok Post Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the board sees a much improved current account deficit
situation. In 1996, the deficit stood at 14 billion US dollars,
equal to 7.9 percent of gross domestic product. While in 1997, the
deficit dropped to 4 billion dollars, or 2.4 percent of GDP, and
is forecast to fall further in 1998 to 1.5 billion dollars, or 1.5
percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth estimate of the board is not far away from
the forecast of the international monetary fund (IMF), which had
forecast a 0.6 percent growth for 1997, and a growth of between 0
and 1 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
In its year-end report published on Tuesday, the Bank of
Thailand put the economic growth for 1997 at zero, and the
economic downturn would reach its worst in the third quarter of
1998, instead of the second quarter, as forecast earlier.
</P>
<P>
In his new year's message on new year's eve, King Bhumibol
Adulyadej urged the people to accept that the new year would be
tough and to prepare themselves to confront hardship with wisdom
and courage.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the country would pull through the
crisis if the people could exercise patience, show the spirit of
sacrifice and unity, and cooperate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
