<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Per-Capita GDP Tops 3,000 Dollars in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
metropolis, has become the first city in the populous country that
registered a per-capita GDP of over 3,000 US dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The figure indicates that Shanghai has hit the national target
of quadrupling the per-capita GDP by the year 2000 three years
ahead of schedule, according to officials from the Shanghai
Municipal Statistical Bureau.
</P>
<P>
However, economists note, the figure is still low as compared
with international standards, particularly those of developed
countries. World average per-capita GDP was 4,470 dollars in as
early as 1994.
</P>
<P>
Bureau statistics also show that the annual GDP exceeded 300
billion yuan (8.32 yuan equals one US dollar) in Shanghai last
year, the first time in its history.
</P>
<P>
The upbeat performance of GDP and per-capita GDP is indicative
of the fact that Shanghai economy has entered a period of fast,
steady growth, economists say.
</P>
<P>
By now, Shanghai has experienced three phases of rapid
per-capita GDP growth: 1978-1988, 1989-1993, and 1994-1997, with
the latest keeping its momentum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
