<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks Required to Report Bad Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines will require banks to make detailed, periodic reports
of their loan exposures, including bad loans, local press reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank deputy governor for bank supervision Alberto Reyes
said the new rules could take effect by March this year, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Excessive non-performing loans is one of the reasons that
caused the current financial crisis sweeping Asia. Amid the
financial storm, the Philippine peso has devaluated by 52 percent
to the current level of around 40 pesos to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Reyes was quoted as saying that the government was taking the
measure to improve "transparency amid eroded confidence" into the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"This is being done by almost all countries," he said, adding
that imposing the regulation would give banking authorities an
"advance warning" on the health of local financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank would probably require commercial banks to
make a report every three months, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the report would have to include the level of bad
loans, restructured loans, loans loss provision for specific
accounts, provision for losses of asset accounts, unbooked
valuation reserves, investment in government securities and other
items.  
</P>
</TEXT>
