<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Vows to Give Priority to Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto vowed today that the government will take every possible
measures to stabilize the country's financial system and restore
the economy to a healthy state.
</P>
<P>
"The government will never allow either a financial crisis or
an economic crisis to start in Japan (and spread to other
countries)," Hashimoto told a news conference marking New Year's
Day.
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly resolved to recover national confidence in the
economy by putting business conditions back on a recovery track
and stabilizing the financial system which constitutes the artery
of the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
A series of collapses of Japanese financial institutions since
the fall of last year has undermined confidence both at home and
abroad in Japan's financial system.
</P>
<P>
Citing the fact that Japan has 1,200 trillion yen (about 9.2
trillion U.S. dollars) in personal financial assets, 800 billion
dollars in net external assets of the state, and the world's
biggest foreign reserves worth more than 200 billion dollars,
Hashimoto urged the public to have confidence in the nation's
financial system.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said he expects a proposed package of economic and
financial measures, featuring 30 trillion yen (about 230.7 billion
dollars) for disposal of failed financial institutions and
protection of depositors, will combine with a proposed 2 trillion
yen (about 153.9 billion dollars) income tax cut to help pave the
way toward economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
To bring about a bright 21st century, Hashimoto said, he will
continue promoting his "six reforms," targeting the
administrative, fiscal, monetary, economic, social security and
education systems, to comprehensively change an arrangement that
is now 50 years old.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, leader of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP),
also expressed his resolve to lead the LDP to a simple majority in
the Upper House in the election scheduled for July. The LDP now
has 117 seats, nine short of a majority, in the 252-seat chamber.
</P>
</TEXT>
