<HEADLINE> Thin Plastic Bags Banned From Beijing's Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The first day of 1998 marks the
end of selling and using thin plastic bags in the Chinese capital
for they cause serious pollution.
</P>
<P>
From the new year, plastic bags thinner than 0.015 millimeters
are banned from the markets and stores of Beijing, according to a
circular issued by the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Food sellers will not be allowed to use such bags. The circular
said many of the bags fail to meet sanitary standards for they
are made from recycled materials and such materials will be
allowed to wrap foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
As the plastic bags, which are hard to disintegrate, are
generally casually discarded around, they cause serious "white
pollution," the circular noted.
</P>
<P>
Citizens of Beijing are encouraged to use thick plastic bags
repeatedly or cloth ones in a bid to reduce pollution.  
</P>
