<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2670 2119 1341 2646 2661 EDS: More to Follow hke010102--News Analysis: 1998, Year of Adjustments for East Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- 1998 is expected to be "a year of
economic adjustments" for East Asia, where reforms and adjustments
aimed to combat a financial crisis have already started and will
be in full swing in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, people celebrate a new year with great joy and
best wishes. But that is not the case for some East Asians when
1998 approaches. They are embracing the new year with mixed
feelings, as the six-month-old crisis is still lingering and lot
of uncertainties are awaiting them with the deepening of painful
reforms and adjustments in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, reforms and adjustments are the only option for the
troubled East Asian nations to clean the mess in their houses.
</P>
<P>
Since a Thai currency crisis spread to other parts of East Asia
last July, the regional financial markets have been in a terrible
mess. Currencies and stocks in Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, the
Philippines, Singapore, South Korea and Japan have fallen to their
record lows in years.
</P>
<P>
Facing the worst crisis in three decades, Thailand, Indonesia
and South Korea have turned to the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) for help. The IMF has put together international bailout
packages for them totaling over 100 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Admitting its misjudgment of the impact of the turmoil, the IMF
recently painted a gloomy picture for East Asian economies hit by
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In its interim World Economic Outlook last month, the IMF
predicted the Japanese economy will grow by only 1.1 percent in
1998 compared with 1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
It slashed its growth estimate for South Korea by 3.5
percentage points to 2.5 percent, and reduced Indonesia's by 4.2
percentage points to 2 percent. Thailand, where the trouble began
last July, will see no economic expansion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Although some economists described the IMF's forecast as too
pessimistic, growth is almost certain to be much slower in the
region in the year because most regional economies have entered a
period of adjustments.
</P>
<P>
In the new year, East Asian countries will restructure their
economies by reforming their fiscal systems, keeping monetary
policy tight and overhauling weak financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
All these move are aimed at eliminating the risks that have
caused the crisis and bringing about a quick and strong recovery,
economists said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: 1998, Year of Adjustments for East Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Last month, the Japanese government announced an economic plan
that will cut income tax by two trillion yen (15.29 billion
dollars) and inject 10 trillion yen of public funds into the
banking system that has recently been rocked by bank and
securities-firm failures.
</P>
<P>
The government said that the plan should alleviate concerns
about Japan's economy, though economists warned the nation's
problem is far from over with these measures.
</P>
<P>
A month ago, the Malaysian government worked out a self-reliant
plan to rescue the country's economy. The government decided to
bail out some ailing companies and force restructuring in others.
</P>
<P>
It will postpone infrastructure projects worth 17 billion
dollars, lower the current-account deficit from 8 percent of GNP
(gross national product) to 4 percent. Of 37 banks in the country,
the weak will be forced to merge with the strong.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the government last week also resorted to
belt-tightening measures to deal with the crisis, though they came
a bit late as some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Ramos administration's tough cost-cutting plan for the new
year include suspension of implementation of new capital projects,
suspension of acquisition of new equipment and motor vehicles,
suspension of foreign trips by government employees, and
suspension of payments of honoraria, overtime payment and
additional benefits to state personnel.
</P>
<P>
The austere plans of Malaysia and the Philippines will
unavoidably affect daily life of their people. But for Thailand,
Indonesia and South Korea, which have received IMF bailout
packages, their reforms and adjustments are more painful as
everything must be done under IMF conditions.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, the 57 billion dollar bailout package offered
by the IMF came with a stiff price of austerity. The country must
keep a tight budget policy so as to relieve burdens of costs on
the restructuring of the finance system.
</P>
<P>
It must narrow tax-break benefits, raise rates of special
excise taxes, transportation taxes and others so as to expand
taxation sources.
</P>
<P>
That is still not enough. South Korea must also slow its
economic growth rate to 3 percent, the slowest in about 20 years;
reduce the current account deficit to below 1 percent of GNP; push
inflation rate below 5 percent; allow domestic interest rates to
rise, and maintain a flexible foreign exchange system.
</P>
<P>
Under the IMF pressure, 14 financial institutions in South
Korea were suspended, while many banks and conglomerates will have
to undertake massive cutbacks and lay-offs.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Indonesia are expected to take the same bitter
pills offered by the IMF in the course of economic adjustments.
The Thai government said last month that it will liquidate nearly
all 58 insolvent finance companies shut down by the central bank,
beginning the biggest ever revamp of the nation's financial
system.
</P>
<P>
As the reforms and adjustments are all austere in nature, the
actions taken by the governments are likely to leave 2 million
people unemployed in the year and create some social problems.
</P>
<P>
However, in a year or two, when adjustments in the region
complete, East Asian economies will become stronger and healthier,
and the social problems will disappear, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
