of Columbia Superior Court by the family of Joviane Waltrick,
seeking 15 million U.S. dollars in damages.
</P>
<P>
Gueorgui Makharadze, 36, a former diplomat for the Republic of
Georgia, whose nation waived his immunity, pleaded guilty in
October to one count of involuntary manslaughter and four counts
of aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian diplomat was sentenced on December 19 to seven to
21 years in prison for the death of Waltrick in the January 3
crash.
</P>
<P>
It will be at least six years before Makharadze, formerly the
second-highest ranking diplomat in the Georgian Embassy, is
eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
The case had stirred debate about diplomatic immunity, which
was waived in the case by Georgia, a former Soviet republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
