<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief to Approve Iraqi Food Distribution Plan Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan would approve Iraq's food and medicine distribution
plan next week, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said today.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the plan, which is originally expected by
Friday this week, is postponed because the annexes to the plan did
not come to the U.N. headquarters in New York from Baghdad until
Wednesday, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The plan details how Iraq will distribute food, medicine and
other humanitarian supplies among its people under the so-called
oil-for-food program, which began last December.
</P>
<P>
The program, which aims to relieve Iraqi people from the
suffering caused by the seven-year sanctions imposed by the U.N.,
allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six
months to buy goods for its people.
</P>
<P>
The U.N Security Council is expected to consider whether to
raise the amount of oil that could be sold by Iraq after Annan
submits a report to it late in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
