<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke010102--News Analysis: 1998, Year of Adjustments for East Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- 1998 is expected to be "a year of
economic adjustments" for East Asia, where reforms and adjustments
aimed to combat a financial crisis have already started and will
be in full swing in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, people celebrate a new year with great joy and
best wishes. But that is not the case for some East Asians when
1998 approaches. They are embracing the new year with mixed
feelings, as the six-month-old crisis is still lingering and lot
of uncertainties are awaiting them with the deepening of painful
reforms and adjustments in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, reforms and adjustments are the only option for the
troubled East Asian nations to clean the mess in their houses.
</P>
<P>
Since a Thai currency crisis spread to other parts of East Asia
last July, the regional financial markets have been in a terrible
mess. Currencies and stocks in Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, the
Philippines, Singapore, South Korea and Japan have fallen to their
record lows in years.
</P>
<P>
Facing the worst crisis in three decades, Thailand, Indonesia
and South Korea have turned to the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) for help. The IMF has put together international bailout
packages for them totaling over 100 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Admitting its misjudgment of the impact of the turmoil, the IMF
recently painted a gloomy picture for East Asian economies hit by
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In its interim World Economic Outlook last month, the IMF
predicted the Japanese economy will grow by only 1.1 percent in
1998 compared with 1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
It slashed its growth estimate for South Korea by 3.5
percentage points to 2.5 percent, and reduced Indonesia's by 4.2
percentage points to 2 percent. Thailand, where the trouble began
last July, will see no economic expansion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Although some economists described the IMF's forecast as too
pessimistic, growth is almost certain to be much slower in the
region in the year because most regional economies have entered a
period of adjustments.
</P>
<P>
In the new year, East Asian countries will restructure their
economies by reforming their fiscal systems, keeping monetary
policy tight and overhauling weak financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
All these move are aimed at eliminating the risks that have
caused the crisis and bringing about a quick and strong recovery,
economists said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Pulls off Surprise Win in Sao Paolo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Emerson Iser
Bem won the annual Sao Silvestre road race run through the streets
of Sao Paulo, Brazil, on Wednesday, beating Kenyan star Paul
Terget to second.
</P>
<P>
He clocked 44 minutes 40 seconds in the 15 kilometers race,
only eight seconds ahead of defending champion Tergat.
</P>
<P>
Tergat, the 10,000 meters world record holder who won the 1995
and 1996 races, appeared to head to his hat-trick victory when he
was 70 meters ahead of Iser Bem with two kilometers left.
</P>
<P>
At this time a spectator doused him with water, disrupting his
rhythm. Organizers said the man had meant to be helpful.
</P>
<P>
Iser Bem then closed the gap on his way to the top of a hill
and then raced away down the final straight to win.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Hendrick Ramaala was third at 44:55 while his
compatriot John Morapedi finished fourth just one second behind.
</P>
<P>
In the women's race, Ecuador's Marta Tenorio won the title in
52:04, almost one minute ahead of Kenyan Lornah Kiplagat in 53:02.
</P>
<P>
Celia Somaggio of Italy was third with four seconds more behind.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 10,000 runners took part in the race this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
