<DOCNO> XIE19980101.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Balloonist to Make Third Around World Try </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Adventurer Steve Fossett
plans to lift off from a sports stadium on Wednesday night in his
third try for a non-stop balloon trip around the world.
</P>
<P>
If all goes as planned, Fossett will sail into the night air
above Busch Stadium in downtown St. Louis between 6 p.m. and 9
p.m. CST (2400 GMT to 0300 GMT Thursday). The trip would last
about 15 days if successful.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old Fossett, a stock options broker, set a record
for time and distance in a balloon last January with a six-day,
16,000-kilometers trip from St. Louis to India. One of the factors
that topped his trip was fuel shortage.
</P>
<P>
This time he is carrying 50 percent more fuel and his balloon
is 28 percent larger at 350,000 cubic feet (9,800 cu meters).
</P>
<P>
He will burn an ethane and propane fuel mixture to heat air
surrounding the helium encapsulated in the mylar-coated balloon
and thus control his altitude.
</P>
<P>
One of Fossett's U.S. rivals in the race to be the first to fly
a balloon around the world, 34-year-old engineer and professional
balloonist Kevin Uliassi, was also reportedly planned to launch
his craft from a rock quarry pit in Rockford, Illinois, after sun
set. 
</P>
</TEXT>
