<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Index of Leading Indicators Rises Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A key measure of future
economic activity rose for the fifth straight month in November,
indicating that the economy will continue expanding into the early
stage of the new year, the Conference Board said today.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based private research group said the Index of
Leading Indicators rose 0.1 percent to 104.6.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board said six of the 10 components in the
leading index fell, adding a hint of caution to the report.
</P>
<P>
Financial markets paid little attention to the report in light
trading ahead of the New Year's holiday. The Dow Jones industrial
average was down 7.72 to 7,908.25, trimming 1997's gain to
1,459.98 points. The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, which began
rising before the report, was up slightly as yields fell below 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The economic expansion is nearing the end of its seventh year,
making it the third-longest in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
In its report today, the Conference Board said big-ticket orders
to manufacturers, excluding defense contracts, were the biggest
contributor to November's rise in the leading index, followed by
growth in the money supply.
</P>
<P>
But stock prices, hurt in November by worries about the effect
of Asia's economic problems on American companies, and new orders
for consumer goods were among the index's six components that fell.
</P>
<P>
The leading index rose 0.1 percent in October and 0.3 percent in
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
