<HEADLINE> US Surplus in Services Trade Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. surplus in services
trade is headed toward 90 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 from 80
billion dollars in 1996, the Journal of Commerce reported today.
</P>
<P>
High-tech companies in the United States brought home 2.3
billion dollars in income from their direct investments in
services operations abroad in 1996, more than 13 times the 1990
level, the paper cited Commerce Department figures.
</P>
<P>
This was achieved when income from all U.S. foreign direct
investments grew 64 percent to 95.1 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
High-tech services produce more related U.S. exports than other
activities abroad, the paper quoted an American Electronics
Association source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Services trade includes trade in travel, telecommunications,
royalties and licensing fees, and banking, financial and computer
services.
</P>
<P>
The services trade surplus is believed to play an important
role in the trade balance of the United States when its trade
deficit stands high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
