<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Stocks Reap Stellar Returns in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chip shares on Wall
Street retreated a bit just as New Year's Eve arrived, but most
stocks finished higher today in a calm conclusion to a volatile,
yet still fruitful year.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 7.72 points to 7,908.25,
trimming 1997's gain to 1,459.98 points. It surrendered a 43-point
gain, but still closed out the year with a robust 22.6 percent
gain.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 0.41 to 970.43,
trimming this year's gain to 229.69, or 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 5.33 to
1,570.36 today, boosting 1997's gain to 279.33 points, or 21.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
All three measures, which have more than doubled since the
start of 1995, have now risen at least 20 percent for three
consecutive years, an unprecedented string.
</P>
<P>
The New York Stock Exchange composite index rose 0.91 to
511.19, up 30.3 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies enjoyed the day's
biggest gains, rising 3.02 to 437.03 to close 1997 with a gain of
20.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the small-company dominated American Stock Exchange
composite index rose 5.70 to 684.61 today, closing out 1997 with
19.6 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outpaced decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the
NYSE, with 1,844 up, 1,112 down and 471 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 465.72 million shares as agains 498.87
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
No clear trend for the new year could be seen as most stocks
drifted in the last session of 1997.
</P>
<P>
There was limited reaction to today's economic news, which
included a report showing that a measure of future economic
activity unexpectedly rose in November, the fifth straight monthly
increase.  
</P>
</TEXT>
