<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Investors' Interest in Equities Grows: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. investors are generally
optimistic about the 1998 stock market after increasing their
exposure to equities in 1997, a survey found.
</P>
<P>
Forty-two percent of investors surveyed said the stock market
will be higher at the end of 1998 than it was in November when the
survey was conducted.
</P>
<P>
The survey was done by OppenheimerFunds, Inc., one of U.S.
leading mutual fund companies, which released a report today.
</P>
<P>
Of the 551 investors surveyed, 55 percent said they have their
portfolios allocated in domestic stocks or stock mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three percent of investors said they increased the
percentage of their portfolios invested in domestic stocks or
stock mutual funds in the last six months when news about the
Asian financial turmoil has spread globally.
</P>
<P>
However, investors remain wary of investing overseas: 49
percent of them do not think it is important to include
international stocks and bonds in a portfolio while 85 percent of
investors believe that it is important to have a diversified
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
About three-fourths of the investors polled said they did not
plan to change the mix of their portfolios in the next six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
