<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Hostage-Taker Surrenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The 42-hour Texas hostage
standoff ended today when the knife-wielding man surrendered to
police after freeing his ex-girlfriend and their two young
daughters whom he took hostage near Dallas, local media reports
said.
</P>
<P>
James Riccardo Lipscomb, 38, released the hostages from a
duplex apartment in the north Dallas suburb of McKinney where he
had held them since Monday night over a domestic dispute.
</P>
<P>
After 42 hours of standoff with police, Lipscomb walked out
the back door of the McKinney apartment with his hands in the air,
kneeled down and was quickly arrested by heavily-armed police.
</P>
<P>
All the hostages, Denise Roach and the three children, aged 7,
9 and 12, were led away to safety.
</P>
<P>
The surrender came about two weeks after Lipscomb's younger
brother, James Monroe Lipscomb Jr., took 80 children and five
adults hostage at a day-care center in the nearby suburb of Plano.
</P>
<P>
That standoff was also triggered by a domestic dispute with an
estranged wife but ended peacefully after 30 hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
